# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: conservation-of-mass
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The forces that cause adhesion and cohesion can be divided into several types.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The intermolecular forces responsible for the function of various kinds of stickers and sticky tape fall into the categories of chemical adhesion, dispersive adhesion, and diffusive adhesion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In addition to the cumulative magnitudes of these intermolecular forces, there are also certain emergent mechanical effects.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Surface energy is conventionally defined as the work that is required to build an area of a particular surface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Another way to view the surface energy is to relate it to the work required to cleave a bulk sample, creating two surfaces.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] If the new surfaces are identical, the surface energy γ of each surface is equal to half the work of cleavage, W: γ = (1/2)W11.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] If the surfaces are unequal, the Young-Dupré equation applies: W12 = γ1 + γ2 – γ12, where γ1 and γ2 are the surface energies of the two new surfaces, and γ12 is the interfacial energy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This methodology can also be used to discuss cleavage that happens in another medium: γ12 = (1/2)W121 = (1/2)W212.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] These two energy quantities refer to the energy that is needed to cleave one species into two pieces while it is contained in a medium of the other species.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Likewise for a three species system: γ13 + γ23 – γ12 = W12 + W33 – W13 – W23 = W132, where W132 is the energy of cleaving species 1 from species 2 in a medium of species 3.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] There is no single theory covering adhesion, and particular mechanisms are specific to particular material scenarios.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Adhesive materials fill the voids or pores of the surfaces and hold surfaces together by interlocking.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Other interlocking phenomena are observed on different length scales.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Sewing is an example of two materials forming a large scale mechanical bond, velcro forms one on a medium scale, and some textile adhesives (glue) form one at a small scale.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Two materials may form a compound at the joint.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The strongest joints are where atoms of the two materials share or swap electrons (known respectively as covalent bonding or ionic bonding).
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] A weaker bond is formed if a hydrogen atom in one molecule is attracted to an atom of nitrogen, oxygen, or fluorine in another molecule, a phenomenon called hydrogen bonding.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Chemical adhesion occurs when the surface atoms of two separate surfaces form ionic, covalent, or hydrogen bonds.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The engineering principle behind chemical adhesion in this sense is fairly straightforward: if surface molecules can bond, then the surfaces will be bonded together by a network of these bonds.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] It bears mentioning that these attractive ionic and covalent forces are effective over only very small distances – less than a nanometer.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This means in general not only that surfaces with the potential for chemical bonding need to be brought very close together, but also that these bonds are fairly brittle, since the surfaces then need to be kept close together.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In dispersive adhesion, also known as physisorption, two materials are held together by van der Waals forces: the attraction between two molecules, each of which has a region of slight positive and negative charge.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In the simple case, such molecules are therefore polar with respect to average charge density, although in larger or more complex molecules, there may be multiple "poles" or regions of greater positive or negative charge.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] These positive and negative poles may be a permanent property of a molecule (Keesom forces) or a transient effect which can occur in any molecule, as the random movement of electrons within the molecules may result in a temporary concentration of electrons in one region (London forces).
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In surface science, the term *adhesion* almost always refers to dispersive adhesion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In a typical solid-liquid-gas system (such as a drop of liquid on a solid surrounded by air) the contact angle is used to evaluate adhesiveness indirectly, while a Centrifugal Adhesion Balance allows for direct quantitative adhesion measurements.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Generally, cases where the contact angle is low are considered of higher adhesion per unit area.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This approach assumes that the lower contact angle corresponds to a higher surface energy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Theoretically, the more exact relation between contact angle and work of adhesion is more involved and is given by the Young-Dupre equation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The contact angle of the three-phase system is a function not only of dispersive adhesion (interaction between the molecules in the liquid and the molecules in the solid) but also cohesion (interaction between the liquid molecules themselves).
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Strong adhesion and weak cohesion results in a high degree of wetting, a lyophilic condition with low measured contact angles.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Conversely, weak adhesion and strong cohesion results in lyophobic conditions with high measured contact angles and poor wetting.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] London dispersion forces are particularly useful for the function of adhesive devices, because they do not require either surface to have any permanent polarity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] They were described in the 1930s by Fritz London, and have been observed by many researchers.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Dispersive forces are a consequence of statistical quantum mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] London theorized that attractive forces between molecules that cannot be explained by ionic or covalent interaction can be caused by polar moments within molecules.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Multipoles could account for attraction between molecules having permanent multipole moments that participate in electrostatic interaction.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] However, experimental data showed that many of the compounds observed to experience van der Waals forces had no multipoles at all.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] London suggested that momentary dipoles are induced purely by virtue of molecules being in proximity to one another.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] While the first term is simply the zero-point energy, the negative second term describes an attractive force between neighboring oscillators.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The same argument can also be extended to a large number of coupled oscillators, and thus skirts issues that would negate the large scale attractive effects of permanent dipoles cancelling through symmetry, in particular.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The additive nature of the dispersion effect has another useful consequence.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Consider a single such dispersive dipole, referred to as the origin dipole.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] When considering identical particles, this is called cohesive force.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] When discussing adhesion, this theory needs to be converted into terms relating to surfaces.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] If there is a net attractive energy of cohesion in a bulk of similar molecules, then cleaving this bulk to produce two surfaces will yield surfaces with a dispersive surface energy, since the form of the energy remain the same.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This theory provides a basis for the existence of van der Waals forces at the surface, which exist between any molecules having electrons.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] These forces are easily observed through the spontaneous jumping of smooth surfaces into contact.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Smooth surfaces of mica, gold, various polymers and solid gelatin solutions do not stay apart when their separating becomes small enough – on the order of 1–10 nm.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] where P is the force (negative for attraction), z is the separation distance, and A is a material-specific constant called the Hamaker constant.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The effect is also apparent in experiments where a polydimethylsiloxane (PDMS) stamp is made with small periodic post structures.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The surface with the posts is placed face down on a smooth surface, such that the surface area in between each post is elevated above the smooth surface, like a roof supported by columns.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Because of these attractive dispersive forces between the PDMS and the smooth substrate, the elevated surface – or "roof" – collapses down onto the substrate without any external force aside from the van der Waals attraction.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Simple smooth polymer surfaces – without any microstructures – are commonly used for these dispersive adhesive properties.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Decals and stickers that adhere to glass without using any chemical adhesives are fairly common as toys and decorations and useful as removable labels because they do not rapidly lose their adhesive properties, as do sticky tapes that use adhesive chemical compounds.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] These forces also act over very small distances – 99% of the work necessary to break van der Waals bonds is done once surfaces are pulled more than a nanometer apart.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] As a result of this limited motion in both the van der Waals and ionic/covalent bonding situations, practical effectiveness of adhesion due to either or both of these interactions leaves much to be desired.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Once a crack is initiated, it propagates easily along the interface because of the brittle nature of the interfacial bonds.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] As an additional consequence, increasing surface area often does little to enhance the strength of the adhesion in this situation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This follows from the aforementioned crack failure – the stress at the interface is not uniformly distributed, but rather concentrated at the area of failure.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Some conducting materials may pass electrons to form a difference in electrical charge at the joint.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This results in a structure similar to a capacitor and creates an attractive electrostatic force between the materials.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Some materials may merge at the joint by diffusion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This may occur when the molecules of both materials are mobile and soluble in each other.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This would be particularly effective with polymer chains where one end of the molecule diffuses into the other material.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] It is also the mechanism involved in sintering.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] When metal or ceramic powders are pressed together and heated, atoms diffuse from one particle to the next.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Diffusive forces are somewhat like mechanical tethering at the molecular level.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Diffusive bonding occurs when species from one surface penetrate into an adjacent surface while still being bound to the phase of their surface of origin.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] One instructive example is that of polymer-on-polymer surfaces.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Diffusive bonding in polymer-on-polymer surfaces is the result of sections of polymer chains from one surface interdigitating with those of an adjacent surface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The freedom of movement of the polymers has a strong effect on their ability to interdigitate, and hence, on diffusive bonding.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] For example, cross-linked polymers are less capable of diffusion and interdigitation because they are bonded together at many points of contact, and are not free to twist into the adjacent surface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Uncrosslinked polymers (thermoplastics), on the other hand are freer to wander into the adjacent phase by extending tails and loops across the interface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Another circumstance under which diffusive bonding occurs is "scission".
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Chain scission is the cutting up of polymer chains, resulting in a higher concentration of distal tails.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The heightened concentration of these chain ends gives rise to a heightened concentration of polymer tails extending across the interface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Scission is easily achieved by ultraviolet irradiation in the presence of oxygen gas, which suggests that adhesive devices employing diffusive bonding actually benefit from prolonged exposure to heat/light and air.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The longer such a device is exposed to these conditions, the more tails are scissed and branch out across the interface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Once across the interface, the tails and loops form whatever bonds are favorable.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In the case of polymer-on-polymer surfaces, this means more van der Waals forces.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] While these may be brittle, they are quite strong when a large network of these bonds is formed.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The outermost layer of each surface plays a crucial role in the adhesive properties of such interfaces, as even a tiny amount of interdigitation – as little as one or two tails of 1.25 angstrom length – can increase the van der Waals bonds by an order of magnitude.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The strength of the adhesion between two materials depends on which of the above mechanisms occur between the two materials, and the surface area over which the two materials contact.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Materials that wet against each other tend to have a larger contact area than those that do not.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Wetting depends on the surface energy of the materials.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Low surface energy materials such as polyethylene, polypropylene, polytetrafluoroethylene and polyoxymethylene are difficult to bond without special surface preparation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Another factor determining the strength of an adhesive contact is its shape.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Adhesive contacts of complex shape begin to detach at the "edges" of the contact area.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The process of destruction of adhesive contacts can be seen in the film.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Recent experimental work has shown that adhesion-force measurements often exhibit non-Gaussian variability, and in some cases the normalized force distribution can be accurately represented using a Beta distribution.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In concert with the primary surface forces described above, there are several circumstantial effects in play.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] While the forces themselves each contribute to the magnitude of the adhesion between the surfaces, the following play a crucial role in the overall strength and reliability of an adhesive device.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Stringing is perhaps the most crucial of these effects, and is often seen on adhesive tapes.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Stringing occurs when a separation of two surfaces is beginning and molecules at the interface bridge out across the gap, rather than cracking like the interface itself.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The most significant consequence of this effect is the restraint of the crack.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] By providing the otherwise brittle interfacial bonds with some flexibility, the molecules that are stringing across the gap can stop the crack from propagating.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Another way to understand this phenomenon is by comparing it to the stress concentration at the point of failure mentioned earlier.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Since the stress is now spread out over some area, the stress at any given point has less of a chance of overwhelming the total adhesive force between the surfaces.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] If failure does occur at an interface containing a viscoelastic adhesive agent, and a crack does propagate, it happens by a gradual process called "fingering", rather than a rapid, brittle fracture.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Stringing can apply to both the diffusive bonding regime and the chemical bonding regime.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The strings of molecules bridging across the gap would either be the molecules that had earlier diffused across the interface or the viscoelastic adhesive, provided that there was a significant volume of it at the interface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The interplay of molecular scale mechanisms and hierarchical surface structures is known to result in high levels of static friction and bonding between pairs of surfaces.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Technologically advanced adhesive devices sometimes make use of microstructures on surfaces, such as tightly packed periodic posts.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] These are biomimetic technologies inspired by the adhesive abilities of the feet of various arthropods and vertebrates (most notably, geckos).
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] By intermixing periodic breaks into smooth, adhesive surfaces, the interface acquires valuable crack-arresting properties.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Because crack initiation requires much greater stress than does crack propagation, surfaces like these are much harder to separate, as a new crack has to be restarted every time the next individual microstructure is reached.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Hysteresis, in this case, refers to the restructuring of the adhesive interface over some period of time, with the result being that the work needed to separate two surfaces is greater than the work that was gained by bringing them together (W > γ1 + γ2).
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] For the most part, this is a phenomenon associated with diffusive bonding.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The more time is given for a pair of surfaces exhibiting diffusive bonding to restructure, the more diffusion will occur, the stronger the adhesion will become.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The aforementioned reaction of certain polymer-on-polymer surfaces to ultraviolet radiation and oxygen gas is an instance of hysteresis, but it will also happen over time without those factors.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In addition to being able to observe hysteresis by determining if W > γ1 + γ2 is true, one can also find evidence of it by performing "stop-start" measurements.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] In these experiments, two surfaces slide against one another continuously and occasionally stopped for some measured amount of time.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Results from experiments on polymer-on-polymer surfaces show that if the stopping time is short enough, resumption of smooth sliding is easy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] If, however, the stopping time exceeds some limit, there is an initial increase of resistance to motion, indicating that the stopping time was sufficient for the surfaces to restructure.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Some atmospheric effects on the functionality of adhesive devices can be characterized by following the theory of surface energy and interfacial tension.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] If γ12 is high, then each species finds it favorable to cohere while in contact with a foreign species, rather than dissociate and mix with the other.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] If this is true, then it follows that when the interfacial tension is high, the force of adhesion is weak, since each species does not find it favorable to bond to the other.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] The interfacial tension of a liquid and a solid is directly related to the liquid's wettability (relative to the solid), and thus one can extrapolate that cohesion increases in non-wetting liquids and decreases in wetting liquids.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] One example that verifies this is polydimethyl siloxane rubber, which has a work of self-adhesion of 43.6 mJ/m2 in air, 74 mJ/m2 in water (a nonwetting liquid) and 6 mJ/m2 in methanol (a wetting liquid).
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This argument can be extended to the idea that when a surface is in a medium with which binding is favorable, it will be less likely to adhere to another surface, since the medium is taking up the potential sites on the surface that would otherwise be available to adhere to another surface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Naturally this applies very strongly to wetting liquids, but also to gas molecules that could adsorb onto the surface in question, thereby occupying potential adhesion sites.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This last point is actually fairly intuitive: Leaving an adhesive exposed to air too long gets it dirty, and its adhesive strength will decrease.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] This is observed in the experiment: when mica is cleaved in air, its cleavage energy, W121 or Wmica/air/mica, is smaller than the cleavage energy in vacuum, Wmica/vac/mica, by a factor of 13.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Lateral adhesion is associated with sliding one object on a substrate, such as sliding a drop on a surface.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] When the two objects are solids, either with or without a liquid between them, the lateral adhesion is described as *friction*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] However, the behavior of lateral adhesion between a drop and a surface is tribologically very different from friction between solids, and the naturally adhesive contact between a flat surface and a liquid drop makes the lateral adhesion in this case, an individual field.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adhesion] Lateral adhesion can be measured using the centrifugal adhesion balance (CAB), which uses a combination of centrifugal and gravitational forces to decouple the normal and lateral forces in the problem.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adolf-eugen-fick] Fick began his work in the formal study of mathematics and physics before realising an aptitude for medicine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adolf-eugen-fick] He then earned his doctorate in medicine from the University of Marburg in 1851.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adolf-eugen-fick] As a fresh medical graduate, he began his work as a prosector.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adolf-eugen-fick] In 1855, he introduced Fick's laws of diffusion, which govern the diffusion of a gas across a fluid membrane.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adolf-eugen-fick] In 1870, he was the first to measure cardiac output, using what is now called the Fick principle.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adolf-eugen-fick] Fick managed to double-publish his law of diffusion, as it applied equally to physiology and physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adolf-eugen-fick] His work led to the development of the direct Fick method for measuring cardiac output.
[src:conservation-of-mass/adolf-eugen-fick] Fick's nephew, Adolf Gaston Eugen Fick, invented the contact lens.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] Born as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg, part of the German Empire, Einstein moved to Switzerland in 1895, forsaking his citizenship the following year.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In 1896, at the age of seventeen, he enrolled in the mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the Swiss federal polytechnic school in Zurich, graduating in 1900.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] He acquired Swiss citizenship a year later, which he kept for the rest of his life, and afterwards secured a permanent position at the Swiss Patent Office in Bern.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, he submitted a successful PhD dissertation to the University of Zurich.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In 1914, he moved to Berlin to join the Prussian Academy of Sciences and the Humboldt University of Berlin, becoming director of the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics in 1917; he also became a Prussian and consequently also German citizen again.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In 1933, while Einstein was visiting the United States, Adolf Hitler came to power in Germany.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] Horrified by the Nazi persecution of his fellow Jews, he decided to remain in the US, and was granted American citizenship in 1940.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] On the eve of World War II, he endorsed a letter to President Franklin D.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] Roosevelt alerting him to the potential German nuclear weapons program and recommending that the US begin similar research, later carried out as the Manhattan Project.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In 1905, sometimes described as his *annus mirabilis* (miracle year), he published four groundbreaking papers.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In them, he outlined a theory of the photoelectric effect, explained Brownian motion, introduced his special theory of relativity, and demonstrated that if the special theory is correct, mass and energy are equivalent to each other.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In 1915, he proposed a general theory of relativity that extended his system of mechanics to incorporate gravitation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] A paper that he published the following year laid out the implications of general relativity for the modeling of the structure and evolution of the universe as a whole.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] It introduced the cosmological constant and is further regarded as the first step in the field of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In the middle part of his career, Einstein made important contributions to statistical mechanics and quantum theory.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] Especially notable was his work on the quantum physics of radiation, in which light consists of particles, subsequently called photons.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] With physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, he laid the groundwork for Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] For much of the last phase of his academic life, Einstein worked on two endeavors that ultimately proved unsuccessful.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] First, he advocated against quantum theory's introduction of fundamental randomness into science's picture of the world, objecting that "God does not play dice".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] Second, he attempted to devise a unified field theory by generalizing his geometric theory of gravitation to include electromagnetism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] As a result, he became increasingly isolated from mainstream modern physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] Many things are named after him, including the element Einsteinium.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p01] In 1999, he was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was born in Ulm as a subject to the Kingdom of Württemberg in the German Empire on 14 March 1879.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His parents, secular Ashkenazi Jews, were Hermann Einstein, a salesman and engineer, and Pauline Koch.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1880, the family moved to Munich's borough of Ludwigsvorstadt-Isarvorstadt, where Einstein's father and his uncle Jakob founded Elektrotechnische Fabrik J.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein & Cie, a company that manufactured electrical equipment based on direct current.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] When he was very young, his parents worried that he had a learning disability because he was very slow to learn to talk.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] When he was five and sick in bed, his father brought him a compass.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] This sparked his lifelong fascination with electromagnetism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Peter's Catholic elementary school in Munich from the age of five.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] When he was eight, he was transferred to the Luitpold Gymnasium, where he received advanced primary and then secondary school education.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1894, Hermann and Jakob's company tendered for a contract to install electric lighting in Munich, but without success—they lacked the capital that would have been required to update their technology from direct current to the more efficient, alternating current alternative.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] The failure of their bid forced them to sell their Munich factory and search for new opportunities elsewhere.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] The Einstein family moved to Italy, first to Milan and a few months later to Pavia, where they settled in Palazzo Cornazzani.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein, then fifteen, stayed behind in Munich in order to finish his schooling.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His father wanted him to study electrical engineering, but he was a fractious pupil who found the Gymnasium's regimen and teaching methods far from congenial.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He later wrote that the school's policy of strict rote learning was harmful to creativity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] At the end of December 1894, a letter from a doctor persuaded the Luitpold's authorities to release him from its care, and he joined his family in Pavia.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] While in Italy as a teenager, he wrote an essay titled "On the Investigation of the State of the Ether in a Magnetic Field".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein excelled at physics and mathematics from an early age, and soon acquired the mathematical expertise normally only found in a child several years his senior.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He began teaching himself algebra, calculus and Euclidean geometry when he was twelve; he made such rapid progress that he discovered an original proof of the Pythagorean theorem before his thirteenth birthday.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] A family tutor, Max Talmud, said that only a short time after he had given the twelve year old Einstein a geometry textbook, the boy "had worked through the whole book.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He thereupon devoted himself to higher mathematics ...
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Soon the flight of his mathematical genius was so high I could not follow." Einstein recorded that he had "mastered integral and differential calculus" while still just fourteen.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His love of algebra and geometry was so great that at twelve, he was already confident that nature could be understood as a "mathematical structure".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] At thirteen, when his range of enthusiasms had broadened to include music and philosophy, Talmud introduced Einstein to Kant's *Critique of Pure Reason*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1895, at the age of sixteen, Einstein sat the entrance examination for the federal polytechnic school (later the Eidgenössische Technische Hochschule, ETH) in Zurich, Switzerland.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He failed to reach the required standard in the general part of the test, but performed with distinction in physics and mathematics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] On the advice of the polytechnic's principal, he completed his secondary education at the Argovian cantonal school (a gymnasium) in Aarau, Switzerland, graduating in 1896.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] While lodging in Aarau with the family of Jost Winteler, he fell in love with Winteler's daughter, Marie.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In January 1896, with his father's approval, Einstein renounced his citizenship of the German Kingdom of Württemberg in order to avoid conscription into military service.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] The *Matura* (graduation for the successful completion of higher secondary schooling), awarded to him in September 1896, acknowledged him to have performed well across most of the curriculum, allotting him a top grade of 6 for history, physics, algebra, geometry, and descriptive geometry.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] At seventeen, he enrolled in the four-year mathematics and physics teaching diploma program at the federal polytechnic school.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He befriended fellow student Marcel Grossmann, who would help him there to get by despite his loose study habits, and later to mathematically underpin his revolutionary insights into physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Marie Winteler, a year older than him, took up a teaching post in Olsberg, Switzerland.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] The five other polytechnic school freshmen following the same course as Einstein included just one woman, a twenty year old Serbian, Mileva Marić.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Over the next few years, the pair spent many hours discussing their shared interests and learning about topics in physics that the polytechnic school's lectures did not cover.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In his letters to Marić, Einstein confessed that exploring science with her by his side was much more enjoyable than reading a textbook in solitude.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually the two students became not only friends, but also lovers.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Historians of physics are divided on the question of the extent to which Marić contributed to the insights of Einstein's *annus mirabilis* publications.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] There is at least some evidence that he was influenced by her scientific ideas, but there are scholars who doubt whether her impact on his thought was of any great significance at all.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Correspondence between Einstein and Marić, discovered and published in 1987, revealed that the couple had a daughter named Lieserl.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] She was born in early 1902 while Marić was visiting her parents in Novi Sad.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić returned to Switzerland the child was no longer with her.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In a letter written in September 1903, Einstein suggested that the girl was either given up for adoption or died of scarlet fever in infancy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić married in January 1903.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In May 1904, their son Hans Albert was born in Bern, Switzerland.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Their son Eduard was born in Zurich in July 1910.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1912, Einstein entered into a relationship with Elsa Löwenthal, who was both his first cousin on his mother's side and his second cousin on his father's.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] When Marić learned of his infidelity soon after moving to Berlin with him in April 1914, she returned to Zurich, taking Hans Albert and Eduard with her.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein and Marić were granted a divorce on 14 February 1919 on the grounds of having lived apart for five years.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] As part of the divorce settlement, Einstein agreed that if he were to win a Nobel Prize, he would give the money that he received to Marić; he won the prize two years later.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1923, he began a relationship with a secretary named Betty Neumann, the niece of his close friend Hans Mühsam.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Löwenthal nevertheless remained loyal to him, accompanying him when he emigrated to the United States in 1933.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1935, she was diagnosed with heart and kidney problems.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] A volume of Einstein's letters released by the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in 2006 added some other women with whom he was romantically involved.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] They included Margarete Lebach (a married Austrian), Estella Katzenellenbogen (the rich owner of a florist business), Toni Mendel (a wealthy Jewish widow) and Ethel Michanowski (a Berlin socialite), with whom he spent time and from whom he accepted gifts while married to Löwenthal.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] After being widowed, Einstein was briefly in a relationship with Margarita Konenkova, thought by some to be a Russian spy; her husband, the Russian sculptor Sergei Konenkov, created the bronze bust of Einstein at the Institute for Advanced Study at Princeton.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Following an episode of acute mental illness at about the age of twenty, Einstein's son Eduard was diagnosed with schizophrenia.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He spent the remainder of his life either in the care of his mother or in temporary confinement in an asylum.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] After her death, he was committed permanently to Burghölzli, the Psychiatric University Hospital in Zurich.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein graduated from the federal polytechnic school in 1900, duly certified as competent to teach mathematics and physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His successful acquisition of Swiss citizenship in February 1901 was not followed by the usual sequel of conscription; the Swiss authorities deemed him medically unfit for military service.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He found that Swiss schools too appeared to have no use for him, failing to offer him a teaching position despite the almost two years that he spent applying for one.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Eventually it was with the help of Marcel Grossmann's father that he secured a post in Bern at the Swiss Patent Office, as an assistant examiner – level III.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Patent applications that landed on Einstein's desk for his evaluation included ideas for a gravel sorter and an electric typewriter.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His employers were pleased enough with his work to make his position permanent in 1903, although they did not think that he should be promoted until he had "fully mastered machine technology".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] It is conceivable that his labors at the patent office had a bearing on his development of his special theory of relativity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He arrived at his revolutionary ideas about space, time and light through thought experiments about the transmission of signals and the synchronization of clocks, matters which also figured in some of the inventions submitted to him for assessment.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1902, Einstein and his friends Conrad Habicht and Maurice Solovine, whom he had met in Bern, formed a group that held regular meetings to discuss science and philosophy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Their choice of a name for their club, the Olympia Academy, was an ironic comment upon its far from Olympian status.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Sometimes they were joined by Marić, who limited her participation in their proceedings to careful listening.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] The thinkers whose works they reflected upon included Henri Poincaré, Ernst Mach and David Hume, all of whom significantly influenced Einstein's own subsequent ideas and beliefs.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's first paper, "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen" ("Conclusions drawn from the phenomena of capillarity"), in which he proposed a model of intermolecular attraction that he afterwards disavowed as worthless, was published in the journal *Annalen der Physik* in 1901.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His 24-page doctoral dissertation also addressed a topic in molecular physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Titled "Eine neue Bestimmung der Moleküldimensionen" ("A New Determination of Molecular Dimensions") and dedicated "Meinem Freunde Herr Dr.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Marcel Grossmann gewidmet" (to his friend Marcel Grossman), it was completed on 30 April 1905 and approved by Professor Alfred Kleiner of the University of Zurich three months later.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] The publications deeply impressed Einstein's contemporaries.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's sabbatical as a civil servant approached its end in 1908, when he secured a junior teaching position at the University of Bern.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1909, a lecture on relativistic electrodynamics that he gave at the University of Zurich, much admired by Alfred Kleiner, led to Zurich's luring him away from Bern with a newly created associate professorship.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Promotion to a full professorship followed in April 1911, when he took up a chair at the German Charles-Ferdinand University in Prague, a move which required him to become an Austrian citizen of the Austro-Hungarian Empire, which was not completed.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His time in Prague saw him producing eleven research papers.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] From 30 October to 3 November 1911, Einstein attended the first Solvay Conference on Physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1912, he returned to his *alma mater*, the ETH Zurich, to take up a chair in theoretical physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His teaching activities there centered on thermodynamics and analytical mechanics, and his research interests included the molecular theory of heat, continuum mechanics and the development of a relativistic theory of gravitation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In his work on the latter topic, he was assisted by his friend Marcel Grossmann, whose knowledge of the kind of mathematics required was greater than his own.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In the spring of 1913, two German visitors, Max Planck and Walther Nernst, called upon Einstein in Zurich in the hope of persuading him to relocate to Berlin.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Their invitation was all the more appealing to him because Berlin happened to be the home of his latest girlfriend, Elsa Löwenthal.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He duly joined the Academy on 24 July 1913, and moved into an apartment in the Berlin district of Dahlem on 1 April 1914.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He was installed in his Humboldt University position shortly thereafter.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] The outbreak of the First World War in July 1914 marked the beginning of Einstein's gradual estrangement from the nation of his birth.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] However, this expression of his doubts about German policy did not prevent him from being elected to a two-year term as president of the German Physical Society in 1916.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] When the Kaiser Wilhelm Institute for Physics opened its doors the following year—its foundation delayed because of the war—Einstein was appointed its first director, just as Planck and Nernst had promised.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein was elected a Foreign Member of the Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1920, and a Foreign Member of the Royal Society in 1921.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Bose derived the Planck spectrum in 1924.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] That same year, Einstein was elected an International Honorary Member of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Britain's closest equivalent of the Nobel award, the Royal Society's Copley Medal, was not hung around Einstein's neck until 1925.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He was elected an International Member of the American Philosophical Society in 1930.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein resigned from the Prussian Academy in March 1933.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His accomplishments in Berlin had included the completion of the general theory of relativity, proving the Einstein–de Haas effect, contributing to the quantum theory of radiation, and the development of Bose–Einstein statistics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1911, he first calculated the gravitational deflection of light passing close to the Sun, a prediction later adjusted upon completion of the general theory of relativity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He reworked his calculation in 1913, having now found a way to model gravitation with the Riemann curvature tensor of a non-Euclidean four-dimensional spacetime.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] A total eclipse of the Sun that took place on 29 May 1919 provided an opportunity to put his theory of gravitational lensing to the test, and observations performed by Sir Arthur Eddington yielded results that were consistent with his calculations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Eddington's work was reported at length in newspapers around the world.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] On 7 November 1919, for example, the leading British newspaper, *The Times*, printed a banner headline that read: "Revolution in Science – New Theory of the Universe – Newtonian Ideas Overthrown".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein began his new life as an intellectual icon in America, where he arrived on 2 April 1921.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He was welcomed to New York City by Mayor John Francis Hylan, and then spent three weeks giving lectures and attending receptions.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He spoke several times at Columbia University and Princeton, and in Washington, he visited the White House with representatives of the National Academy of Sciences.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He returned to Europe via London, where he was the guest of the philosopher and statesman Viscount Haldane.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He used his time in the British capital to meet several people prominent in British scientific, political or intellectual life, and to deliver a lecture at King's College.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In July 1921, he published an essay, "My First Impression of the U.S.A.", in which he sought to sketch the American character.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He wrote of his transatlantic hosts in highly approving terms: "What strikes a visitor is the joyous, positive attitude to life ...
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In 1922, Einstein's travels were to the old world rather than the new.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He devoted six months to a tour of Asia that saw him speaking in Japan, Singapore and Sri Lanka (then known as Ceylon).
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] After his first public lecture in Tokyo, he met Emperor Yoshihito and his wife at the Imperial Palace, with thousands of spectators thronging the streets in the hope of catching a glimpse of him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] (In a letter to his sons, he wrote that Japanese people seemed to him to be generally modest, intelligent and considerate, and to have a true appreciation of art.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] But his picture of them in his diary was less flattering: "[the] intellectual needs of this nation seem to be weaker than their artistic ones – natural disposition?" His journal also contains views of China and India which were uncomplimentary.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Of Chinese people, he wrote that "even the children are spiritless and look obtuse...
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] It would be a pity if these Chinese supplant all other races.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] For the likes of us the mere thought is unspeakably dreary".) He was greeted with even greater enthusiasm on the last leg of his tour, in which he spent twelve days in Mandatory Palestine, newly entrusted to British rule by the League of Nations in the aftermath of the First World War.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Sir Herbert Samuel, the British High Commissioner, welcomed him with a degree of ceremony normally only accorded to a visiting head of state, including a cannon salute.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] One reception held in his honor was stormed by people determined to hear him speak: he told them that he was happy that Jews were beginning to be recognized as a force in the world.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] On April 6, 1922, during a visit to Paris, Einstein engaged in a debate on relativity with the philosopher Henri Bergson.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] This dispute has had widespread ramifications for the humanities and was an academic *cause célèbre* at the time.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's decision to tour the eastern hemisphere in 1922 meant that he was unable to go to Stockholm in the December of that year to participate in the Nobel prize ceremony.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His place at the traditional Nobel banquet was taken by a German diplomat, who gave a speech praising him not only as a physicist but also as a campaigner for peace.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] A two-week visit to Spain that he undertook in 1923 saw him collecting another award, a membership of the Spanish Academy of Sciences signified by a diploma handed to him by King Alfonso XIII.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] He was appointed as a German delegate rather than as a representative of Switzerland because of the machinations of two Catholic activists, Oskar Halecki and Giuseppe Motta.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] By persuading Secretary General Eric Drummond to deny Einstein the place on the committee reserved for a Swiss thinker, they created an opening for Gonzague de Reynold, who used his League of Nations position as a platform from which to promote traditional Catholic doctrine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein's former physics professor Hendrik Lorentz and the Polish chemist Marie Curie were also members of the committee.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In March and April 1925, Einstein and his wife visited South America, where they spent about a week in Brazil, a week in Uruguay and a month in Argentina.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] In December 1930, Einstein began another significant sojourn in the United States, drawn back to the US by the offer of a two month research fellowship at the California Institute of Technology.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Caltech supported him in his wish that he should not be exposed to quite as much attention from the media as he had experienced when visiting the US in 1921, and he therefore declined all the invitations to receive prizes or make speeches that his admirers poured down upon him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] But he remained willing to allow his fans at least some of the time with him that they requested.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] After arriving in New York City, Einstein was taken to various places and events, including Chinatown, a lunch with the editors of *The New York Times*, and a performance of *Carmen* at the Metropolitan Opera, where he was cheered by the audience on his arrival.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] During the days following, he was given the keys to the city by Mayor Jimmy Walker and met Nicholas Murray Butler, the president of Columbia University, who described Einstein as "the ruling monarch of the mind".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Harry Emerson Fosdick, pastor at New York's Riverside Church, gave Einstein a tour of the church and showed him a full-size statue that the church made of Einstein, standing at the entrance.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Also during his stay in New York, he joined a crowd of 15,000 people at Madison Square Garden during a Hanukkah celebration.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Einstein next traveled to California, where he met Caltech president and Nobel laureate Robert A.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] His friendship with Millikan was "awkward", as Millikan "had a penchant for patriotic militarism", where Einstein was a pronounced pacifist.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] During an address to Caltech's students, Einstein noted that science was often inclined to do more harm than good.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] This aversion to war also led Einstein to befriend author Upton Sinclair and film star Charlie Chaplin, both noted for their pacifism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Carl Laemmle, head of Universal Studios, gave Einstein a tour of his studio and introduced him to Chaplin.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] They had an instant rapport, with Chaplin inviting Einstein and his wife, Elsa, to his home for dinner.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p02] Chaplin said Einstein's outward persona, calm and gentle, seemed to conceal a "highly emotional temperament", from which came his "extraordinary intellectual energy".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin's film *City Lights* was to premiere a few days later in Hollywood, and Chaplin invited Einstein and Elsa to join him as his special guests.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Walter Isaacson, Einstein's biographer, described this as "one of the most memorable scenes in the new era of celebrity".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin visited Einstein at his home on a later trip to Berlin and recalled his "modest little flat" and the piano at which he had begun writing his theory.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Chaplin speculated that it was "possibly used as kindling wood by the Nazis".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein and Chaplin were cheered at the premiere of the film.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In February 1933, while on a visit to the United States, Einstein knew he could not return to Germany with the rise to power of the Nazis under Germany's new chancellor, Adolf Hitler.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] While at American universities in early 1933, he undertook his third two-month visiting professorship at the California Institute of Technology in Pasadena.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In February and March 1933, the Gestapo repeatedly raided his family's apartment in Berlin.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He and his wife Elsa returned to Europe in March, and during the trip, they learned that the German Reichstag had passed the Enabling Act on 23 March, transforming Hitler's government into a *de facto* legal dictatorship, and that they would not be able to proceed to Berlin.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Later on, they heard that their cottage had been raided by the Nazis and Einstein's personal sailboat confiscated.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Upon landing in Antwerp, Belgium on 28 March, Einstein immediately went to the German consulate and surrendered his passport, formally renouncing his German citizenship.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] The renunciation was at first refused, but the Nazi government finally revoked his citizenship on 24 March 1934.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] The Nazis later sold his boat and converted his cottage into a Hitler Youth camp.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In April 1933, Einstein discovered that the new German government had passed laws barring Jews from holding any official positions, including teaching at universities.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Historian Gerald Holton describes how, with "virtually no audible protest being raised by their colleagues", thousands of Jewish scientists were suddenly forced to give up their university positions and their names were removed from the rolls of institutions where they were employed.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In a subsequent letter to physicist and friend Max Born, who had already emigrated from Germany to England, Einstein wrote, "...
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was now without a permanent home, unsure where he would live and work, and equally worried about the fate of countless other scientists still in Germany.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Aided by the Academic Assistance Council, founded in April 1933 by British Liberal politician William Beveridge to help academics escape Nazi persecution, Einstein was able to leave Germany.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He rented a house in De Haan, Belgium, where he lived for a few months.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In late July 1933, he visited England for about six weeks at the invitation of the British Member of Parliament Commander Oliver Locker-Lampson, who had become friends with him in the preceding years.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson invited him to stay near his Cromer home in a secluded wooden cabin on Roughton Heath in the Parish of Roughton, Norfolk.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] To protect Einstein, Locker-Lampson had two bodyguards watch over him; a photo of them carrying shotguns and guarding Einstein was published in the *Daily Herald* on 24 July 1933.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson took Einstein to meet Winston Churchill at his home, and later, Austen Chamberlain and former Prime Minister Lloyd George.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein asked them to help bring Jewish scientists out of Germany.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] British historian Martin Gilbert notes that Churchill responded immediately, and sent his friend physicist Frederick Lindemann to Germany to seek out Jewish scientists and place them in British universities.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Churchill later observed that as a result of Germany having driven the Jews out, they had lowered their "technical standards" and put the Allies' technology ahead of theirs.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein later contacted leaders of other nations, including Turkey's Prime Minister, İsmet İnönü, to whom he wrote in September 1933, requesting placement of unemployed German-Jewish scientists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] As a result of Einstein's letter, Jewish invitees to Turkey eventually totaled over "1,000 saved individuals".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Locker-Lampson also submitted a bill to parliament to extend British citizenship to Einstein, during which period Einstein made a number of public appearances describing the crisis brewing in Europe.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In one of his speeches he denounced Germany's treatment of Jews, while at the same time he introduced a bill promoting Jewish citizenship in Palestine, as they were being denied citizenship elsewhere.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In his speech he described Einstein as a "citizen of the world" who should be offered a temporary shelter in the UK.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Both bills failed, however, and Einstein then accepted an earlier offer from the Institute for Advanced Study, in Princeton, New Jersey, US, to become a resident scholar.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] On 3 October 1933, Einstein delivered a speech on the importance of academic freedom before a packed audience at the Royal Albert Hall in London, with *The Times* reporting he was wildly cheered throughout.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Four days later he returned to the US and took up a position at the Institute for Advanced Study, noted for having become a refuge for scientists fleeing Nazi Germany.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] At the time, most American universities, including Harvard, Princeton and Yale, had minimal or no Jewish faculty or students, as a result of their Jewish quotas, which lasted until the late 1940s.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was still undecided about his future.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's affiliation with the Institute for Advanced Study would last until his death in 1955.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He was one of the four first selected (along with John von Neumann, Kurt Gödel and Hermann Weyl) at the new Institute.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He soon developed a close friendship with Gödel; the two would take long walks together discussing their work.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Bruria Kaufman, his assistant, later became a physicist.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] During this period, Einstein tried to develop a unified field theory and to refute the accepted interpretation of quantum physics, both unsuccessfully.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He lived in Princeton at his home from 1935 onwards.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] The Albert Einstein House was made a National Historic Landmark in 1976.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In 1939, a group of Hungarian scientists that included émigré physicist Leó Szilárd attempted to alert Washington, D.C. to ongoing Nazi atomic bomb research.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He was asked to lend his support by writing a letter, with Szilárd, to President Franklin D.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Roosevelt, recommending the US pay attention and engage in its own nuclear weapons research.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] The letter is believed to be "arguably the key stimulus for the U.S. adoption of serious investigations into nuclear weapons on the eve of the U.S. entry into World War II".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In addition to the letter, Einstein used his connections with the Belgian royal family and the Belgian queen mother to get access with a personal envoy to the White House's Oval Office.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Some say that as a result of Einstein's letter and his meetings with Roosevelt, the US entered the "race" to develop the bomb, drawing on its "immense material, financial, and scientific resources" to initiate the Manhattan Project.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] For Einstein, "war was a disease ... [and] he called for resistance to war." By signing the letter to Roosevelt, some argue he went against his pacifist principles.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein became an American citizen in 1940.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Not long after settling into his career at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey, he expressed his appreciation of the meritocracy in American culture compared to Europe.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He recognized the "right of individuals to say and think what they pleased" without social barriers.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] As a result, individuals were encouraged, he said, to be more creative, a trait he valued from his early education.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein joined the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People (NAACP) in Princeton, where he campaigned for the civil rights of African Americans.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He considered racism America's "worst disease", seeing it as "handed down from one generation to the next".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] As part of his involvement, he corresponded with civil rights activist W.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Du Bois and was prepared to testify on his behalf during his trial as an alleged foreign agent in 1951.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] When Einstein offered to be a character witness for Du Bois, the judge decided to drop the case.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In 1946, Einstein visited Lincoln University in Pennsylvania, a historically black college, where he was awarded an honorary degree.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Lincoln was the first university in the United States to grant college degrees to African Americans; alumni include Langston Hughes and Thurgood Marshall.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein gave a speech about racism in America, adding, "I do not intend to be quiet about it." A resident of Princeton recalls that Einstein had once paid the college tuition for a black student.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein has said, "Being a Jew myself, perhaps I can understand and empathize with how black people feel as victims of discrimination".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Isaacson writes that "When Marian Anderson, the black contralto, came to Princeton for a concert in 1937, the Nassau Inn refused her a room.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] So Einstein invited her to stay at his house on Main Street, in what was a deeply personal as well as symbolic gesture ...
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In 1918, Einstein was one of the signatories of the founding proclamation of the German Democratic Party, a liberal party.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Later in his life, Einstein's political view was in favor of socialism and critical of capitalism, which he detailed in his essays such as "Why Socialism?".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] His opinions on the Bolsheviks also changed with time.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In 1925, he criticized them for not having a "well-regulated system of government" and called their rule a "regime of terror and a tragedy in human history".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein offered and was called on to give judgments and opinions on matters often unrelated to theoretical physics or mathematics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He strongly advocated the idea of a democratic global government that would check the power of nation-states in the framework of a world federation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote "I advocate world government because I am convinced that there is no other possible way of eliminating the most terrible danger in which man has ever found himself." The FBI created a secret dossier on Einstein in 1932; by the time of his death, it was 1,427 pages long.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was deeply impressed by Mahatma Gandhi, with whom he corresponded.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He described Gandhi as "a role model for the generations to come".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] The initial connection was established on 27 September 1931, when Wilfrid Israel took his Indian guest V.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram to his friend Einstein's summer home in the town of Caputh to meet him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Sundaram was Gandhi's disciple and special envoy, whom Wilfrid Israel met while visiting India and visiting the Indian leader's home in 1925.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] During the visit, Einstein wrote a short letter to Gandhi that was delivered to him through Sundaram, and Gandhi responded quickly with his own letter.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Although in the end Einstein and Gandhi were unable to meet as they had hoped, the direct connection between them was established through Wilfrid Israel.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein, a Jew, was a figurehead leader in the establishment of the Hebrew University of Jerusalem, which opened in 1925.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Earlier, in 1921, he was asked by the biochemist and president of the World Zionist Organization, Chaim Weizmann, to help raise funds for the planned university.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He made suggestions for the creation of an Institute of Agriculture, a Chemical Institute and an Institute of Microbiology in order to fight the various ongoing epidemics such as malaria, which he called an "evil" that was undermining a third of the country's development.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He also promoted the establishment of an Oriental Studies Institute, to include language courses given in both Hebrew and Arabic.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was not a nationalist and opposed the creation of an independent Jewish state.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He felt that the waves of arriving Jews of the Aliyah could live alongside existing Arabs in Palestine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] The state of Israel was established without his help in 1948; Einstein was limited to a marginal role in the Zionist movement.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Afterward, Einstein adopted a practical attitude, understanding that "there is no going back", and the new state must be supported.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Upon the death of Israeli president Weizmann in November 1952, Prime Minister David Ben-Gurion offered Einstein the largely ceremonial position of President of Israel at the urging of Ezriel Carlebach.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] The offer was presented by Israel's ambassador in Washington, Abba Eban, who explained that the offer "embodies the deepest respect which the Jewish people can repose in any of its sons".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein wrote that he was "deeply moved", but "at once saddened and ashamed" that he could not accept it.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein did not want the office, and the Israeli government did not want him to accept, but felt obliged to make the offer.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Yitzhak Navon, Ben-Gurion's political secretary, and later president, reports Ben-Gurion as saying "Tell me what to do if he says yes!
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] I've had to offer the post to him because it's impossible not to.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Per Lee Smolin, "I believe what allowed Einstein to achieve so much was primarily a moral quality.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He simply cared far more than most of his colleagues that the laws of physics have to explain everything in nature coherently and consistently." Einstein expounded his spiritual outlook in a wide array of writings and interviews.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He said he had sympathy for the impersonal pantheistic God of Baruch Spinoza's philosophy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He did not believe in a personal god who concerns himself with fates and actions of human beings, a view which he described as naïve.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He clarified, however, that "I am not an atheist", preferring to call himself an agnostic, or a "deeply religious nonbeliever".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He wrote that "A spirit is manifest in the laws of the universe—a spirit vastly superior to that of man, and one in the face of which we with our modest powers must feel humble.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein was primarily affiliated with non-religious humanist and Ethical Culture groups in both the UK and US.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He served on the advisory board of the First Humanist Society of New York, and was an honorary associate of the Rationalist Association, which publishes *New Humanist* in Britain.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] For the 75th anniversary of the New York Society for Ethical Culture, he stated that the idea of Ethical Culture embodied his personal conception of what is most valuable and enduring in religious idealism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein had been sympathetic toward vegetarianism for a long time.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He became a vegetarian himself only during the last part of his life.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In March 1954 he wrote in a letter: "So I am living without fats, without meat, without fish, but am feeling quite well this way.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein developed an appreciation for music at an early age.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] His mother played the piano reasonably well and wanted her son to learn the violin, not only to instill in him a love of music but also to help him assimilate into German culture.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] According to conductor Leon Botstein, Einstein began playing when he was 5.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] However, he did not enjoy it at that age.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] When he turned 13, he discovered Mozart's violin sonatas, whereupon he became enamored of Mozart's compositions and studied music more willingly.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein taught himself to play without "ever practicing systematically".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He said that "love is a better teacher than a sense of duty".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] At the age of 17, he was heard by a school examiner in Aarau while playing Beethoven's violin sonatas.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] The examiner stated afterward that his playing was "remarkable and revealing of 'great insight'".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] What struck the examiner, writes Botstein, was that Einstein "displayed a deep love of the music, a quality that was and remains in short supply.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Music took on a pivotal and permanent role in Einstein's life from that period on.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Although the idea of becoming a professional musician himself was not on his mind at any time, among those with whom Einstein played chamber music were a few professionals, including Kurt Appelbaum, and he performed for private audiences and friends.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Chamber music had also become a regular part of his social life while living in Bern, Zurich, and Berlin, where he played with Max Planck and his son, among others.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He is sometimes erroneously credited as the editor of the 1937 edition of the Köchel catalog of Mozart's work; that edition was prepared by Alfred Einstein, who may have been a distant relation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In 1931, while engaged in research at the California Institute of Technology, he visited the Zoellner family conservatory in Los Angeles, where he played some of Beethoven and Mozart's works with members of the Zoellner Quartet.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Near the end of his life, when the young Juilliard Quartet visited him in Princeton, he played his violin with them, and the quartet was "impressed by Einstein's level of coordination and intonation".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] On 17 April 1955, Einstein experienced internal bleeding caused by the rupture of an abdominal aortic aneurysm, which had previously been reinforced surgically by Rudolph Nissen in 1948.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] He took the draft of a speech he was preparing for a television appearance commemorating the state of Israel's seventh anniversary with him to the hospital, but he did not live to complete it.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein refused surgery, saying, "I want to go when I want.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] It is tasteless to prolong life artificially.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] I will do it elegantly." He died in the Princeton Hospital early the next morning at the age of 76, having continued to work until near the end.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] During the autopsy, the pathologist Thomas Stoltz Harvey removed Einstein's brain for preservation without the permission of his family, in the hope that the neuroscience of the future would be able to discover what made Einstein so intelligent.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein's remains were cremated in Trenton, New Jersey, and his ashes were scattered at an undisclosed location.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] In a memorial lecture delivered on 13 December 1965 at UNESCO headquarters, nuclear physicist J.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Robert Oppenheimer summarized his impression of Einstein as a person: "He was almost wholly without sophistication and wholly without worldliness ...
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p03] Einstein bequeathed his personal archives, library, and intellectual assets to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem in Israel.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Throughout his life, Einstein published hundreds of books and articles.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He published more than 300 scientific papers and 150 non-scientific ones.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] On 5 December 2014, universities and archives announced the release of Einstein's papers, comprising more than 30,000 unique documents.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to the work he did by himself, he also collaborated with other scientists on additional projects, including the Bose–Einstein statistics, the Einstein refrigerator and others.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's first paper, submitted in 1900 to *Annalen der Physik*, was on capillary attraction.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] It was published in 1901 with the title "Folgerungen aus den Capillaritätserscheinungen", which translates as "Conclusions from the capillarity phenomena".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Two papers he published in 1902–1903 (thermodynamics) attempted to interpret atomic phenomena from a statistical point of view.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] These papers were the foundation for the 1905 paper on Brownian motion, which showed that Brownian movement can be construed as firm evidence that molecules exist.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] His research in 1903 and 1904 was mainly concerned with the effect of finite atomic size on diffusion phenomena.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein returned to the problem of thermodynamic fluctuations, giving a treatment of the density variations in a fluid at its critical point.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Ordinarily, the density fluctuations are controlled by the second derivative of the free energy with respect to the density.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] At the critical point, this derivative is zero, leading to large fluctuations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The effect of density fluctuations is that light of all wavelengths is scattered, making the fluid look milky white.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein relates this to Rayleigh scattering, which is what happens when the fluctuation size is much smaller than the wavelength, and which explains why the sky is blue.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein quantitatively derived critical opalescence from a treatment of density fluctuations, and demonstrated how both the effect and Rayleigh scattering originate from the atomistic constitution of matter.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The *Annus Mirabilis* papers are four articles pertaining to the photoelectric effect (which gave rise to quantum theory), Brownian motion, the special theory of relativity, and *E* = *mc*2 that Einstein published in the *Annalen der Physik* scientific journal in 1905.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] These four works contributed substantially to the foundation of modern physics and changed views on space, time, and matter.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's "*Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper*" ("On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies") was received on 30 June 1905 and published 26 September of that same year.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] It reconciled conflicts between Maxwell's equations (the laws of electricity and magnetism) and the laws of Newtonian mechanics by introducing changes to the laws of mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Observationally, the effects of these changes are most apparent at high speeds (where objects are moving at speeds close to the speed of light).
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The theory developed in this paper later became known as Einstein's special theory of relativity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This paper predicted that, when measured in the frame of a relatively moving observer, a clock carried by a moving body would appear to slow down, and the body itself would contract in its direction of motion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This paper also argued that the idea of a luminiferous aether—one of the leading theoretical entities in physics at the time—was superfluous.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In his paper on mass–energy equivalence, Einstein produced *E* = *mc*2 as a consequence of his special relativity equations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's 1905 work on relativity remained controversial for many years, but was accepted by leading physicists, starting with Max Planck.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein originally framed special relativity in terms of kinematics (the study of moving bodies).
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Hermann Minkowski reinterpreted special relativity in geometric terms as a theory of spacetime.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein adopted Minkowski's formalism in his 1915 general theory of relativity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity (GR) is a theory of gravitation that was developed by Einstein between 1907 and 1915.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] According to it, the observed gravitational attraction between masses results from the warping of spacetime by those masses.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity has developed into an essential tool in modern astrophysics; it provides the foundation for the current understanding of black holes, regions of space where gravitational attraction is so strong that not even light can escape.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] As Einstein later said, the reason for the development of general relativity was that the preference of inertial motions within special relativity was unsatisfactory, while a theory which from the outset prefers no state of motion (even accelerated ones) should appear more satisfactory.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, in 1907 he published an article on acceleration under special relativity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In that article titled "On the Relativity Principle and the Conclusions Drawn from It", he argued that free fall is really inertial motion, and that for a free-falling observer the rules of special relativity must apply.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This argument is called the equivalence principle.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In the same article, Einstein also predicted the phenomena of gravitational time dilation, gravitational redshift and gravitational lensing.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1911, Einstein published another article "On the Influence of Gravitation on the Propagation of Light" expanding on the 1907 article, in which he estimated the amount of deflection of light by massive bodies.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Thus, the theoretical prediction of general relativity could for the first time be tested experimentally.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1916, Einstein predicted gravitational waves, ripples in the curvature of spacetime which propagate as waves, traveling outward from the source, transporting energy as gravitational radiation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The existence of gravitational waves is possible under general relativity due to its Lorentz invariance which brings the concept of a finite speed of propagation of the physical interactions of gravity with it.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] By contrast, gravitational waves cannot exist in the Newtonian theory of gravitation, which postulates that the physical interactions of gravity propagate at infinite speed.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The first, indirect, detection of gravitational waves came in the 1970s through observation of a pair of closely orbiting neutron stars, PSR B1913+16.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The explanation for the decay in their orbital period was that they were emitting gravitational waves.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's prediction was confirmed on 11 February 2016, when researchers at LIGO published the first observation of gravitational waves, detected on Earth on 14 September 2015, nearly one hundred years after the prediction.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] While developing general relativity, Einstein became confused about the gauge invariance in the theory.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He formulated an argument that led him to conclude that a general relativistic field theory is impossible.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He gave up looking for fully generally covariant tensor equations and searched for equations that would be invariant under general linear transformations only.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In June 1913, the Entwurf ('draft') theory was the result of these investigations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] As its name suggests, it was a sketch of a theory, less elegant and more difficult than general relativity, with the equations of motion supplemented by additional gauge fixing conditions.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] After more than two years of intensive work, Einstein realized that the hole argument was mistaken and abandoned the theory in November 1915.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, Einstein applied the general theory of relativity to the structure of the universe as a whole.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He discovered that the general field equations predicted a universe that was dynamic, either contracting or expanding.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] As observational evidence for a dynamic universe was lacking at the time, Einstein introduced a new term, the cosmological constant, into the field equations, in order to allow the theory to predict a static universe.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The modified field equations predicted a static universe of closed curvature, in accordance with Einstein's understanding of Mach's principle in these years.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This model became known as the Einstein World or Einstein's static universe.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This paper is widely regarded as marking the emergence of modern theoretical cosmology.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Following the discovery of the recession of the galaxies by Edwin Hubble in 1929, Einstein abandoned his static model of the universe, and proposed two dynamic models of the cosmos, the Friedmann–Einstein universe of 1931 and the Einstein–de Sitter universe of 1932.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In each of these models, Einstein discarded the cosmological constant, claiming that it was "in any case theoretically unsatisfactory".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In many Einstein biographies, it is claimed that Einstein referred to the cosmological constant in later years as his "biggest blunder", based on a letter George Gamow claimed to have received from him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The astrophysicist Mario Livio has cast doubt on this claim.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In late 2013, a team led by the Irish physicist Cormac O'Raifeartaigh discovered evidence that, shortly after learning of Hubble's observations of the recession of the galaxies, Einstein considered a steady-state model of the universe.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In a hitherto overlooked manuscript, apparently written in early 1931, Einstein explored a model of the expanding universe in which the density of matter remains constant due to a continuous creation of matter, a process that he associated with the cosmological constant.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] It thus appears that Einstein considered a steady-state model of the expanding universe many years before Hoyle, Bondi and Gold.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] However, Einstein's steady-state model contained a fundamental flaw and he quickly abandoned the idea.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] General relativity includes a dynamical spacetime, so it is difficult to see how to identify the conserved energy and momentum.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Noether's theorem allows these quantities to be determined from a Lagrangian with translation invariance, but general covariance makes translation invariance into something of a gauge symmetry.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The energy and momentum derived within general relativity by Noether's prescriptions do not make a real tensor for this reason.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein argued that this is true for a fundamental reason: the gravitational field could be made to vanish by a choice of coordinates.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He maintained that the non-covariant energy momentum pseudotensor was, in fact, the best description of the energy momentum distribution in a gravitational field.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] While the use of non-covariant objects like pseudotensors was criticized by Erwin Schrödinger and others, Einstein's approach has been echoed by physicists including Lev Landau and Evgeny Lifshitz.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1935, Einstein collaborated with Nathan Rosen to produce a model of a wormhole, often called Einstein–Rosen bridges.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] His motivation was to model elementary particles with charge as a solution of gravitational field equations, in line with the program outlined in the paper "Do Gravitational Fields play an Important Role in the Constitution of the Elementary Particles?".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] These solutions cut and pasted Schwarzschild black holes to make a bridge between two patches.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Because these solutions included spacetime curvature without the presence of a physical body, Einstein and Rosen suggested that they could provide the beginnings of a theory that avoided the notion of point particles.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] However, it was later found that Einstein–Rosen bridges are not stable.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In order to incorporate spinning point particles into general relativity, the affine connection needed to be generalized to include an antisymmetric part, called the torsion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This modification was made by Einstein and Cartan in the 1920s.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In general relativity, gravitational force is reimagined as curvature of spacetime.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] A curved path like an orbit is not the result of a force deflecting a body from an ideal straight-line path, but rather the body's attempt to fall freely through a background that is itself curved by the presence of other masses.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The geodesic equation covers the former aspect, stating that freely falling bodies follow lines that are as straight as possible in a curved spacetime.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein regarded this as an "independent fundamental assumption" that had to be postulated in addition to the field equations in order to complete the theory.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Believing this to be a shortcoming in how general relativity was originally presented, he wished to derive it from the field equations themselves.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Since the equations of general relativity are non-linear, a lump of energy made out of pure gravitational fields, like a black hole, would move on a trajectory which is determined by the Einstein field equations themselves, not by a new law.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Accordingly, Einstein proposed that the field equations would determine the path of a singular solution, like a black hole, to be a geodesic.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Both physicists and philosophers have often repeated the assertion that the geodesic equation can be obtained from applying the field equations to the motion of a gravitational singularity, but this claim remains disputed.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In a 1905 paper, Einstein postulated that light itself consists of localized particles (*quanta*).
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's light quanta were nearly universally rejected by all physicists, including Max Planck and Niels Bohr.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This idea only became universally accepted in 1919, with Robert Millikan's detailed experiments on the photoelectric effect, and with the measurement of Compton scattering.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein concluded that each wave of frequency *f* is associated with a collection of photons with energy *hf* each, where *h* is the Planck constant.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He did not say much more, because he was not sure how the particles were related to the wave.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] But he did suggest that this idea would explain certain experimental results, notably the photoelectric effect.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Light quanta were dubbed *photons* by Gilbert N.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1907, Einstein proposed a model of matter where each atom in a lattice structure is an independent harmonic oscillator.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In the Einstein model, each atom oscillates independently—a series of equally spaced quantized states for each oscillator.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein was aware that getting the frequency of the actual oscillations would be difficult, but he nevertheless proposed this theory because it was a particularly clear demonstration that quantum mechanics could solve the specific heat problem in classical mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1924, Einstein received a description of a statistical model from Indian physicist Satyendra Nath Bose, based on a counting method that assumed that light could be understood as a gas of indistinguishable particles.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein noted that Bose's statistics applied to some atoms as well as to the proposed light particles, and submitted his translation of Bose's paper to the *Zeitschrift für Physik*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also published his own articles describing the model and its implications, among them the Bose–Einstein condensate phenomenon that some particulates should appear at very low temperatures.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] It was not until 1995 that the first such condensate was produced experimentally by Eric Allin Cornell and Carl Wieman using ultra-cooling equipment built at the NIST–JILA laboratory at the University of Colorado at Boulder.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Bose–Einstein statistics are now used to describe the behaviors of any assembly of bosons.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's sketches for this project may be seen in the Einstein Archive in the library of the Leiden University.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Although the patent office promoted Einstein to Technical Examiner Second Class in 1906, he had not given up on academia.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, he became a *Privatdozent* at the University of Bern.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This paper introduced the *photon* concept and inspired the notion of wave–particle duality in quantum mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein saw this wave–particle duality in radiation as concrete evidence for his conviction that physics needed a new, unified foundation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In a series of works completed from 1911 to 1913, Planck reformulated his 1900 quantum theory and introduced the idea of zero-point energy in his "second quantum theory".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Soon, this idea attracted the attention of Einstein and his assistant Otto Stern.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Assuming the energy of rotating diatomic molecules contains zero-point energy, they then compared the theoretical specific heat of hydrogen gas with the experimental data.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] However, after publishing the findings, they promptly withdrew their support, because they no longer had confidence in the correctness of the idea of zero-point energy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1917, at the height of his work on relativity, Einstein published an article in *Physikalische Zeitschrift* that proposed the possibility of stimulated emission, the physical process that makes possible the maser and the laser.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This article showed that the statistics of absorption and emission of light would only be consistent with Planck's distribution law if the emission of light into a mode with n photons would be enhanced statistically compared to the emission of light into an empty mode.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This paper was enormously influential in the later development of quantum mechanics, because it was the first paper to show that the statistics of atomic transitions had simple laws.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein discovered Louis de Broglie's work and supported his ideas, which were received skeptically at first.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In another major paper from this era, Einstein observed that de Broglie waves could explain the quantization rules of Bohr and Sommerfeld.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This paper would inspire Schrödinger's work of 1926.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein played a major role in developing quantum theory, beginning with his 1905 paper on the photoelectric effect.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] However, he became displeased with modern quantum mechanics as it had evolved after 1925, despite its acceptance by other physicists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He was skeptical that the randomness of quantum mechanics was fundamental rather than the result of determinism, stating that God "is not playing at dice".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Until the end of his life, he continued to maintain that quantum mechanics was incomplete.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The Bohr–Einstein debates were a series of public disputes about quantum mechanics between Einstein and Niels Bohr, who were two of its founders.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates are remembered because of their importance to the philosophy of science.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Their debates would influence later interpretations of quantum mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein never fully accepted quantum mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] While he recognized that it made correct predictions, he believed a more fundamental description of nature must be possible.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Over the years he presented multiple arguments to this effect, but the one he preferred most dated to a debate with Bohr in 1930.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein suggested a thought experiment in which two objects are allowed to interact and then moved apart a great distance from each other.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The quantum-mechanical description of the two objects is a mathematical entity known as a wavefunction.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] If the wavefunction that describes the two objects before their interaction is given, then the Schrödinger equation provides the wavefunction that describes them after their interaction.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] But because of what would later be called quantum entanglement, measuring one object would lead to an instantaneous change of the wavefunction describing the other object, no matter how far away it is.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Moreover, the choice of which measurement to perform upon the first object would affect what wavefunction could result for the second object.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein reasoned that no influence could propagate from the first object to the second instantaneously fast.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Indeed, he argued, physics depends on being able to tell one thing apart from another, and such instantaneous influences would call that into question.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Because the true "physical condition" of the second object could not be immediately altered by an action done to the first, Einstein concluded, the wavefunction could not be that true physical condition, only an incomplete description of it.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] A more famous version of this argument came in 1935, when Einstein published a paper with Boris Podolsky and Nathan Rosen that laid out what would become known as the EPR paradox.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In this thought experiment, two particles interact in such a way that the wavefunction describing them is entangled.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Then, no matter how far the two particles were separated, a precise position measurement on one particle would imply the ability to predict, perfectly, the result of measuring the position of the other particle.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Likewise, a precise momentum measurement of one particle would result in an equally precise prediction for of the momentum of the other particle, without needing to disturb the other particle in any way.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] They argued that no action taken on the first particle could instantaneously affect the other, since this would involve information being transmitted faster than light, which is forbidden by the theory of relativity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] But quantum mechanics considers these two observables incompatible and thus does not associate simultaneous values for both to any system.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein, Podolsky, and Rosen therefore concluded that quantum theory does not provide a complete description of reality.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1964, John Stewart Bell carried the analysis of quantum entanglement much further.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He deduced that if measurements are performed independently on the two separated particles of an entangled pair, then the assumption that the outcomes depend upon hidden variables within each half implies a mathematical constraint on how the outcomes on the two measurements are correlated.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This constraint would later be called a Bell inequality.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Bell then showed that quantum physics predicts correlations that violate this inequality.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Consequently, the only way that hidden variables could explain the predictions of quantum physics is if they are "nonlocal", which is to say that somehow the two particles are able to interact instantaneously no matter how widely they ever become separated.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Bell argued that because an explanation of quantum phenomena in terms of hidden variables would require nonlocality, the EPR paradox "is resolved in the way which Einstein would have liked least".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Despite this, and although Einstein personally found the argument in the EPR paper overly complicated, that paper became among the most influential papers published in *Physical Review*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] It is considered a centerpiece of the development of quantum information theory.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Encouraged by his success with general relativity, Einstein sought an even more ambitious geometrical theory that would treat gravitation and electromagnetism as aspects of a single entity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1950, he described his unified field theory in a *Scientific American* article titled "On the Generalized Theory of Gravitation".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] His attempt to find the most fundamental laws of nature won him praise but not success: a particularly conspicuous blemish of his model was that it did not accommodate the strong and weak nuclear forces, neither of which was well understood until many years after his death.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Although most researchers now believe that Einstein's approach to unifying physics was mistaken, his goal of a theory of everything is one to which his successors still aspire.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein conducted other investigations that were unsuccessful and abandoned.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] These pertain to force, superconductivity, and other research.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In addition to longtime collaborators Leopold Infeld, Nathan Rosen, Peter Bergmann and others, Einstein also had some one-shot collaborations with various scientists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1908, Owen Willans Richardson predicted that a change in the magnetic moment of a free body will cause this body to rotate.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This effect is a consequence of the conservation of angular momentum and is strong enough to be observable in ferromagnetic materials.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein and Wander Johannes de Haas published two papers in 1915 claiming the first experimental observation of the effect.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Measurements of this kind demonstrate that the phenomenon of magnetization is caused by the alignment (polarization) of the angular momenta of the electrons in the material along the axis of magnetization.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] These measurements also allow the separation of the two contributions to the magnetization: that which is associated with the spin and with the orbital motion of the electrons.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The Einstein-de Haas experiment is the only experiment conceived, realized and published by Albert Einstein himself.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] A complete original version of the Einstein-de Haas experimental equipment was donated by Geertruida de Haas-Lorentz, wife of de Haas and daughter of Lorentz, to the Ampère Museum in Lyon France in 1961 where it is currently on display.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] It was lost among the museum's holdings and was rediscovered in 2023.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1926, Einstein and his former student Leó Szilárd co-invented (and in 1930, patented) the Einstein refrigerator.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] This absorption refrigerator was then revolutionary for having no moving parts and using only heat as an input.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] On 11 November 1930, U.S. patent 1,781,541 was awarded to Einstein and Leó Szilárd for the refrigerator.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Their invention was not immediately put into commercial production, but the most promising of their patents were acquired by the Swedish company Electrolux.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein also invented an electromagnetic pump, sound reproduction device, and several other household devices.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] While traveling, Einstein wrote daily to his wife Elsa and adopted stepdaughters Margot and Ilse.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The letters were included in the papers bequeathed to the Hebrew University of Jerusalem.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Margot Einstein permitted the personal letters to be made available to the public, but requested that it not be done until twenty years after her death (she died in 1986).
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Barbara Wolff, of the Hebrew University's Albert Einstein Archives, told the BBC that there are about 3,500 pages of private correspondence written between 1912 and 1955.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In his final four years, Einstein was involved with the establishment of the Albert Einstein College of Medicine in New York City.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1979, the Albert Einstein Memorial was unveiled outside the National Academy of Sciences building in Washington, D.C. for the Einstein centenary.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein can be seen holding a paper with three of his most important equations: for the photoelectric effect, general relativity and mass-energy equivalence.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein's right of publicity was litigated in 2015 in a federal district court in California.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Although the court initially held that the right had expired, that ruling was immediately appealed, and the decision was later vacated in its entirety.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The underlying claims between the parties in that lawsuit were ultimately settled.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The right is enforceable, and the Hebrew University of Jerusalem is the exclusive representative of that right.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Corbis, successor to The Roger Richman Agency, licenses the use of his name and associated imagery, as agent for the university.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in the Chugach Mountains of Alaska was named in 1955.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Mount Einstein in New Zealand's Paparoa Range was named after him in 1970 by the Department of Scientific and Industrial Research.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, Einstein was named *Time*'s Person of the Century.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In 1999, a survey of the top 100 physicists voted for Einstein as the "greatest physicist ever", while a parallel survey of rank-and-file physicists gave the top spot to Isaac Newton, with Einstein second.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Simmons ranked Einstein second after Newton in *The Scientific 100*, based on a qualitative assessment in which he ordered the scientists according to overall influence, and noted that the work of Einstein "forms the source of twentieth-century physics".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The International Union of Pure and Applied Physics declared 2005 the "World Year of Physics", also known as "Einstein Year", in recognition of Einstein's "miracle year" in 1905.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] It was also declared the "International Year of Physics" by the United Nations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein became one of the most famous scientific celebrities after the confirmation of his general theory of relativity in 1919.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Although most of the public had little understanding of his work, he was widely recognized and admired.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] In the period before World War II, *The New Yorker* published a vignette in their "The Talk of the Town" feature saying that Einstein was so well known in America that he would be stopped on the street by people wanting him to explain "that theory".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Eventually he came to cope with unwanted enquirers by pretending to be someone else: "Pardon me, sorry!
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein has been the subject of or inspiration for many novels, films, plays, and works of music.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] He is a favorite model for depictions of absent-minded professors; his expressive face and distinctive hairstyle have been widely copied and exaggerated.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] *Time* magazine's Frederic Golden wrote that Einstein was "a cartoonist's dream come true".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] His intellectual achievements and originality made *Einstein* broadly synonymous with *genius*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Many popular quotations are often misattributed to him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einstein received numerous awards and honors, and in 1922, he was awarded the 1921 Nobel Prize in Physics "for his services to Theoretical Physics, and especially for his discovery of the law of the photoelectric effect".
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] The Nobel committee decided that none of the nominations in 1921 met the criteria set by Alfred Nobel, so the 1921 prize was carried forward and awarded to Einstein in 1922.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] Einsteinium, a synthetic chemical element, was named in his honor in 1955, a few months after his death.
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] (Public Domain) *Einstein, Albert (1926).
[src:conservation-of-mass/albert-einstein-p04] London & New York: The Encyclopædia Britannica Company. pp.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Alchemists attempted to purify, mature, and perfect certain materials.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Common aims were chrysopoeia, the transmutation of "base metals" (e.g., lead) into "noble metals" (particularly gold); the creation of an elixir of immortality; and the creation of panaceas able to cure any disease.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The perfection of the human body and soul was thought to result from the alchemical *magnum opus* ("Great Work").
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The concept of creating the philosopher's stone was variously connected with all of these projects.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Islamic and European alchemists developed a basic set of laboratory techniques, theories, and terms, some of which are still in use today.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] They did not abandon the Ancient Greek philosophical idea that everything is composed of four elements, and they tended to guard their work in secrecy, often making use of cyphers and cryptic symbolism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] In Europe, the 12th-century translations of medieval Islamic works on science and the rediscovery of Aristotelian philosophy gave birth to a flourishing tradition of Latin alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] This late medieval tradition of alchemy would go on to play a significant role in the development of early modern science (particularly chemistry and medicine).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Modern discussions of alchemy are generally split into an examination of its exoteric practical applications and its esoteric spiritual aspects, despite criticisms by scholars such as Eric J.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Holmyard and Marie-Louise von Franz that they should be understood as complementary.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The former is pursued by historians of the physical sciences, who examine the subject in terms of early chemistry, medicine, and charlatanism, and the philosophical and religious contexts in which these events occurred.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The latter interests historians of esotericism, psychologists, and some philosophers and spiritualists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The subject has also made an ongoing impact on literature and the arts.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The word alchemy comes from Old French *alkimie*, used in Medieval Latin as *alchymia*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] This name was itself adopted from the Arabic word *al-kīmiyā* (الكيمياء).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The Arabic *al-kīmiyā* in turn was a borrowing of the Late Greek term *khēmeía* (χημεία), also spelled *khumeia* (χυμεία) and *khēmía* (χημία), with *al-* being the Arabic definite article 'the'.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Together this association can be interpreted as 'the process of transmutation by which to fuse or reunite with the divine or original form'.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Several etymologies have been proposed for the Greek term.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The first was proposed by Zosimos of Panopolis (3rd–4th centuries), who derived it from the name of a book, the *Khemeu*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Hermann Diels argued in 1914 that it rather derived from χύμα, used to describe metallic objects formed by casting.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] Others trace its roots to the Egyptian name *kēme*, meaning 'black earth', which refers to the fertile and auriferous soil of the Nile valley, as opposed to red desert sand.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] According to the Egyptologist Wallis Budge, the Arabic word **al-kīmiya*ʾ* actually means "the Egyptian [science]", borrowing from the Coptic word for "Egypt", **kēme** (or its equivalent in the Mediaeval Bohairic dialect of Coptic, **khēme**).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] This Coptic word derives from Demotic **kmỉ**, itself from ancient Egyptian **kmt**.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p01] The ancient Egyptian word referred to both the country and the colour "black" (Egypt was the "black Land", by contrast with the "red Land", the surrounding desert).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Alchemy comprises a plurality of philosophical traditions extending across approximately four millennia and spanning three continents.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The marked tendency of these traditions toward esoteric and highly symbolic modes of expression renders it difficult to reconstruct their patterns of mutual influence and genealogical relationships.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Chinese alchemy was closely connected to Taoism and Indian alchemy with the Dharmic faiths.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In contrast, Western alchemy developed its philosophical system mostly independent of but influenced by various Western religions.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] It is still an open question whether these three strands share a common origin, or to what extent they influenced each other.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The start of Western alchemy may generally be traced to Hellenistic Egypt, where the city of Alexandria was a center of alchemical knowledge, and retained its pre-eminence through most of the Greek and Roman periods.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Following the work of André-Jean Festugière, modern scholars see alchemical practice in the Roman Empire as originating from the Egyptian goldsmith's art, Greek philosophy and different religious traditions.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Tracing the origins of the alchemical art in Egypt is complicated by the pseudepigraphic nature of texts from the Greek alchemical corpus.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The treatises of Zosimos of Panopolis, the earliest historically attested author (fl. c.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] 300), can help in situating the other authors.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Zosimus based his work on that of older alchemical authors, such as Mary the Jewess, Pseudo-Democritus, and Agathodaimon, but very little is known about any of these authors.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The most complete of their works, the *Four Books* of Pseudo-Democritus, were probably written in the first century AD.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Recent scholarship tends to emphasize the testimony of Zosimus, who traced the alchemical arts back to Egyptian metallurgical and ceremonial practices.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] It has also been argued that early alchemical writers borrowed the vocabulary of Greek philosophical schools but did not implement any of its doctrines in a systematic way.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Zosimos of Panopolis wrote in the *Final Abstinence* (a.k.a. the *Final Count*) that the ancient practice of "tinctures" (the technical Greek term for the alchemical arts) had been taken over by certain "demons" who taught the art only to those who offered them sacrifices.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Since Zosimos also called the demons "the guardians of places" (οἱ κατὰ τόπον ἔφοροι, *hoi katà tópon éphoroi*) and those who offered them sacrifices "priests" (ἱερέα, *hieréa*), it is fairly clear that he was referring to the gods of Egypt and their priests.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] While critical of the kind of alchemy he associated with the Egyptian priests and their followers, Zosimos nonetheless saw the tradition's recent past as rooted in the rites of the Egyptian temples.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Zosimos of Panopolis asserted that alchemy dated back to Pharaonic Egypt where it was the domain of the priestly class, though there is little to no evidence for his assertion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Alchemical writers used classical figures from Greek (e.g., Hades), Roman (e.g., Lucius), and Egyptian mythology to illuminate their works and allegorize alchemical transmutation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] These included the pantheon of gods related to the classical planets, Isis, Osiris, Jason, and many others.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The central figure in the mythology of alchemy is Hermes Trismegistus (Ἑρμῆς ὁ Τρισμέγιστος, 'Hermes the Thrice-Greatest').
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] His name is derived from the god Thoth and his Greek counterpart, Hermes.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Hermes and his caduceus or serpent-staff, were among alchemy's principal symbols.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] According to Clement of Alexandria, he wrote what were called the "forty-two books of Hermes", covering all fields of knowledge.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The *Hermetica* are a compendium of texts attributed to Hermes Trismegistus.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Many of them have close historical connections with Western alchemical philosophy and practice (which was sometimes called the Hermetic philosophy by its practitioners).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] By modern convention, the *Hermetica* is usually subdivided into two main categories: the "technical" and "religio-philosophical" *Hermetica*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The "technical" *Hermetica* deals with alchemy, astrology, medicine, pharmacology, and magic.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Its oldest parts were written in Greek and may go back as far as the second or third century BC.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Many of the texts in the "technical" *Hermetica* were later translated, first into Arabic and then into Latin, often being extensively revised and expanded throughout the centuries.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Some of them were also originally written in Arabic.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In other cases their status as an original work or translation remains unclear.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] These Arabic and Latin Hermetic texts were widely copied throughout the Middle Ages.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The most famous of these texts is the *Emerald Tablet*, also known as the *Smaragdine Table* or the *Tabula Smaragdina*, a compact and cryptic text.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The earliest known versions of it are four Arabic recensions preserved in mystical and alchemical treatises between the 8th and 10th centuries AD—chiefly the *Secret of Creation* (سر الخليقة, *Sirr al-Khalīqa*) and the *Secret of Secrets* (سرّ الأسرار, *Sirr al-Asrār*).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Medieval commentators such as Ortolanus interpreted it as a "foundational text" of alchemical instructions for producing the philosopher's stone and making gold.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The dawn of Western alchemy is sometimes associated with that of metallurgy, extending back to 3500 BC.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Many writings were lost when the Roman emperor Diocletian ordered the burning of alchemical books after suppressing a revolt in Alexandria (AD 292).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Few original Egyptian documents on alchemy have survived, most notable among them the Stockholm papyrus and the Leyden papyrus X.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Dating from AD 250 to 300, they contained recipes for dyeing and making artificial gemstones, cleaning and fabricating pearls, and manufacturing of imitation gold and silver.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] These writings lack the mystical, philosophical elements of alchemy, but do contain the works of Bolus of Mendes (or Pseudo-Democritus), which aligned these recipes with theoretical knowledge of astrology and the classical elements.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Between the time of Bolus and Zosimos, the change took place that transformed this metallurgy into a Hermetic art.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Alexandria acted as a melting pot for philosophies of Pythagoreanism, Platonism, Stoicism, and Gnosticism that formed the origin of alchemy's character.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] An important example of alchemy's roots in Greek philosophy, originated by Empedocles and developed by Aristotle, was that all things in the universe were formed from only four elements: earth, air, water, and fire.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] According to Aristotle, each element had a sphere to which it belonged and to which it would return if left undisturbed.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Later alchemists extensively developed the mystical aspects of this concept.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Alchemy coexisted alongside emerging Christianity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Lactantius believed Hermes Trismegistus had prophesied its birth.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Augustine of Hippo later affirmed this in the 4th and 5th centuries, but also condemned Trismegistus for idolatry.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Examples of pagan, Christian, and Jewish alchemists can be found during this period.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Most of the Greco-Roman alchemists preceding Zosimos are known only by pseudonyms, such as Moses of Alexandria, Isis, Cleopatra the Alchemist, Pseudo-Democritus, and Ostanes.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Other authors such as Komarios and Chymes are known only through surviving fragments of text.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] After AD 400, Greek alchemical writers occupied themselves solely in commenting on the works of these predecessors.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] By the middle of the 7th century, alchemy was almost an entirely mystical discipline.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] It was at that time that Khalid Ibn Yazid sparked its migration from Alexandria to the Islamic world, facilitating the translation and preservation of Greek alchemical texts in the 8th and 9th centuries.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Greek alchemy was preserved in medieval Byzantine manuscripts after the fall of Roman Egypt, yet historians have only relatively recently begun to study and development of Greek alchemy in the Byzantine period.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The 2nd millennium BC Vedas describe a connection between eternal life and gold.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Buddhist texts from the 2nd to 5th centuries mention the transmutation of base metals to gold.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] According to some scholars Greek alchemy may have influenced Indian alchemy but there are no hard evidences to back this claim.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The goals of alchemy in India included the creation of a divine body (*divya-deham*) and immortality while still embodied (*jīvan-mukti*).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Sanskrit alchemical texts include much material on the manipulation of mercury and sulphur, that are homologized with the semen of the god Śiva and the menstrual blood of the goddess Devī.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Some early alchemical writings seem to have their origins in the Kaula tantric schools associated to the teachings of the personality of Matsyendranath.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Other early writings are found in the Jaina medical treatise *Kalyāṇakārakam* of Ugrāditya, written in South India in the early 9th century.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Two famous early Indian alchemical authors were Nāgārjuna Siddha and Nityanātha Siddha.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] His book *Rasendramangalam* is an example of Indian alchemy and medicine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Nityanātha Siddha wrote *Rasaratnākara*, which was also a highly influential work.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In Sanskrit, *rasa* translates to "mercury", and Nāgārjuna Siddha was said to have developed a method of converting mercury into gold.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] An example of academic scholarship on Indian alchemy is *The Alchemical Body* by Indologist David Gordon White.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] A modern bibliography on Indian alchemical studies has been written by White.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The contents of 39 Sanskrit alchemical treatises have been analysed in detail in Gerrit Jan Meulenbeld's *History of Indian Medical Literature* (*HIML*).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The discussion of these works in the *HIML* gives a summary of the contents of each work, their special features, and where possible the evidence concerning their dating.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Chapter 13 of the *HIML*, *Various works on rasaśāstra and ratnaśāstra* ('Various works on alchemy and gems') gives brief details of another 655 treatises.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In some cases, Meulenbeld gives notes on the contents and authorship of these works; in other cases references are made only to the unpublished manuscripts of these titles.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] A great deal remains to be discovered about Indian alchemical literature.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] After the fall of the Roman Empire, the focus of alchemical development moved to the Islamic World.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Much more is known about Islamic alchemy because it was better documented: indeed, most of the earlier writings that have come down through the years were preserved as Arabic translations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The word *alchemy* itself was derived from the Arabic word *al-kīmiyā* (الكيمياء).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The early Islamic world was a melting pot for alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Platonic and Aristotelian thought, which had already been somewhat appropriated into Hermetic science, continued to be assimilated during the late 7th and early 8th centuries through Syriac translations and scholarship.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the late ninth and early tenth centuries, the Arabic works attributed to Jābir ibn Hayyān (Latinized as "Geber" or "Geberus") introduced a new approach to alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Islamic philosophers also made great contributions to alchemical Hermeticism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The most influential author in this regard was arguably ibn Hayyan. ibn Hayyan's ultimate goal was *takwin*, the artificial creation of life in the alchemical laboratory—up to and including human life.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] He analysed each Aristotelian element in terms of four basic qualities of *hotness*, *coldness*, *dryness*, and *moistness*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] According to ibn Hayyan, in each metal two of these qualities were interior and two were exterior.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] For example, lead was externally cold and dry, while gold was hot and moist.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Thus, ibn Hayyan theorized, by rearranging the qualities of one metal, a different metal would result.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] By this reasoning, the search for the philosopher's stone was introduced to Western alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Ibn Hayyan developed an elaborate numerology whereby the root letters of a substance's name in Arabic, when treated with various transformations, held correspondences to the element's physical properties.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The atomic theory of corpuscularianism, where all physical bodies possess an inner and outer layer of minute particles or corpuscles, also has its origins in the work of ibn Hayyan.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] From the 9th to 14th centuries, alchemical theories faced criticism from a variety of practical Muslim chemists, including Al-Kindi, Abū al-Rayhān al-Bīrūnī, Avicenna and Ibn Khaldun.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In particular, they wrote refutations against the idea of the transmutation of metals.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] From the 14th century onwards, many materials and practices originally belonging to Indian alchemy (*Rasayana*) were assimilated in the Persian texts written by Muslim scholars.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Researchers have found evidence that Chinese alchemists and philosophers discovered complex mathematical phenomena that were shared with Arab alchemists during the medieval period.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Discovered first in China before the Common Era, the "magic square of three" was propagated to followers of Jabir ibn Hayyan at some point over the proceeding several hundred years.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Other commonalities shared between the two alchemical schools of thought include discrete naming for ingredients and heavy influence from the natural elements.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The Silk Road provided a clear path for the exchange of goods, ideas, ingredients, religion, and many other aspects of life with which alchemy is intertwined.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Whereas European alchemy eventually centered on the transmutation of base metals into noble metals, Chinese alchemy had a more obvious connection to medicine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The philosopher's stone of European alchemists can be compared to the elixir of life sought by Chinese alchemists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the Hermetic view, these two goals were not unconnected, and the philosopher's stone was often equated with the universal panacea; therefore, the two traditions may have had more in common than initially appears.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] As early as 317 AD, Ge Hong documented the use of metals, minerals, and elixirs in early Chinese medicine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Hong identified three ancient Chinese documents—titled the *Scripture of Great Clarity*, the *Scripture of the Nine Elixirs*, and the *Scripture of the Golden Liquor*—as texts containing fundamental alchemical information.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] He also described alchemy, along with meditation, as the sole spiritual practices that could allow one to gain immortality or to transcend to a higher state of being.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In his work *Inner Chapters of the Book of the Master Who Embraces Spontaneous Nature* (317 AD), Hong argued that alchemical solutions such as elixirs were preferable to traditional medicinal treatment due to the spiritual protection they could provide.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the centuries following Ge Hong's death, the emphasis placed on alchemy as a spiritual practice among Chinese Taoists was reduced.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In 499 AD, Tao Hongjing refuted Hong's statement that alchemy is as important a spiritual practice as Shangqing meditation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] While Hongjing did not deny the power of alchemical elixirs to grant immortality or provide divine protection, he ultimately found the *Scripture of the Nine Elixirs* to be ambiguous and spiritually unfulfilling, aiming to implement more accessible practising techniques.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the early 700s, *Neidan* (a.k.a. internal alchemy) was adopted by Daoists as a new form of alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] *Neidan* emphasized appeasing the inner gods that inhabit the human body by practising alchemy with compounds naturally found in the body, rather than the mixing of natural resources that was so emphasized in early Dao alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] For example, saliva was often considered nourishment for the inner gods and did not require any conscious alchemical reaction to produce.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The inner gods were not thought of as physical presences occupying each person, but rather a collection of deities that are each said to represent and protect a specific body part or region.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Although those who practised *Neidan* prioritized meditation over external alchemical strategies, many of the same elixirs and constituents from previous Daoist alchemical schools of thought continued to be utilized in tandem with meditation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Eternal life remained a consideration for *Neidan* alchemists, as it was believed that one would become immortal if an inner god were to be immortalized within them through spiritual fulfilment.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Chinese alchemy was closely connected to Taoist techniques in traditional Chinese medicine like acupuncture and moxibustion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the early Song dynasty, followers of this Taoist idea—chiefly the elite and upper class—would ingest mercuric sulfide, which, though tolerable in low levels, led many to suicide.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The introduction of alchemy to Latin Europe may be dated to 11 February 1144, with the completion of Robert of Chester's translation of the *Liber de compositione alchemiae* (Book on the Composition of Alchemy) from an Arabic work attributed to Khalid ibn Yazid.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Although European craftsmen and technicians pre-existed, Robert notes in his preface that alchemy (here still referring to the elixir rather than to the art itself) was unknown in Latin Europe at the time of his writing.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The translation of Arabic texts concerning numerous disciplines including alchemy flourished in 12th-century Toledo, Spain, through contributors like Gerard of Cremona and Adelard of Bath.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Translations of the time included the Turba Philosophorum, and the works of Avicenna and Muhammad ibn Zakariya al-Razi.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] These brought with them many new words to the European vocabulary for which there was no previous Latin equivalent.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Alcohol, carboy, elixir, and athanor are examples.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Meanwhile, theologian contemporaries of the translators made strides towards the reconciliation of faith and experimental rationalism, thereby priming Europe for the influx of alchemical thought.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The 11th-century theologian Anselm of Canterbury put forth the opinion that faith and rationalism were compatible and encouraged rationalism in a Christian context.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the early 12th century, Peter Abelard followed Anselm's work, laying down the foundation for acceptance of Aristotelian thought before the first works of Aristotle had reached the West.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the early 13th century, Robert Grosseteste used Abelard's methods of analysis and added the use of observation, experimentation, and conclusions when conducting scientific investigations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Grosseteste also did much work to reconcile Platonic and Aristotelian thinking.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Through much of the 12th and 13th centuries, alchemical knowledge in Europe remained centered on translations, and new Latin contributions were not made.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The efforts of the translators were succeeded by that of the encyclopaedists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the 13th century, Albertus Magnus and Roger Bacon were the most notable of these, their work summarizing and explaining the newly imported alchemical knowledge in Aristotelian terms.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Albertus Magnus, a Dominican friar, is known to have written works such as the *Book of Minerals* where he observed and commented on the operations and theories of alchemical authorities like Hermes Trismegistus, pseudo-Democritus, and unnamed alchemists of his time.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Albertus critically compared these to the writings of Aristotle and Avicenna, where they concerned the transmutation of metals.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] From the time shortly after his death through to the 15th century, more than 28 alchemical tracts were misattributed to him, a common practice giving rise to his reputation as an accomplished alchemist.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Likewise, alchemical texts have been attributed to Albert's student Thomas Aquinas.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Bacon's writings integrated morality, salvation, alchemy, and the prolongation of life.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] His correspondence with Clement highlighted this, noting the importance of alchemy to the papacy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Like the Greeks before him, Bacon acknowledged the division of alchemy into practical and theoretical spheres.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] He noted that the theoretical lay outside the scope of Aristotle, the natural philosophers, and all Latin writers of his time.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The practical confirmed the theoretical, and Bacon advocated its uses in natural science and medicine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In later European legend, he became an archmage.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In particular, along with Albertus Magnus, he was credited with the forging of a brazen head capable of answering its owner's questions.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Soon after Bacon, the influential work of Pseudo-Geber (sometimes identified as Paul of Taranto) appeared.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] His *Summa Perfectionis* remained a staple summary of alchemical practice and theory through the medieval and renaissance periods.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] It was notable for its inclusion of practical chemical operations alongside sulphur-mercury theory, and the unusual clarity with which they were described.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] By the end of the 13th century, alchemy had developed into a fairly structured system of belief.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Adepts believed in the macrocosm-microcosm theories of Hermes; namely, that processes that affect minerals and other substances could have an effect on the human body (for example, if one could learn the secret of purifying gold, one could use the technique to purify the human soul).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] They believed in the four elements and the four qualities as described above, and they had a strong tradition of cloaking their written ideas in a labyrinth of coded jargon set with traps to mislead the uninitiated.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Finally, the alchemists practised their art: they actively experimented with chemicals and made observations and theories about how the universe operated.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Their entire philosophy revolved around their belief that the human soul was divided within itself after the fall of Adam.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] By purifying the two parts of humankind's soul, humans could be reunited with God.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the 14th century, alchemy became more accessible to Europeans outside the confines of Latin-speaking churchmen and scholars.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Alchemical discourse shifted from scholarly philosophical debate to an exposed social commentary on the alchemists themselves.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Dante Alighieri, Piers Plowman, and Geoffrey Chaucer all painted unflattering pictures of alchemists as thieves and liars.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Pope John XXII's 1317 edict *Spondent quas non-exhibent* forbade the false promises of transmutation made by pseudo-alchemists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Roman Catholic Inquisitor General Nicholas Eymerich's *Directorium Inquisitorum*, written in 1376, associated alchemy with the performance of demonic rituals, which Eymerich differentiated from magic performed in accordance with Christian scripture.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] This did not, however, lead to any change in the Inquisition's monitoring or prosecution of alchemists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In 1404, Henry IV of England banned the practice of multiplying metals by the passing of the Gold and Silver Act 1403 (5 Hen.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] 4) (although it was possible to buy a licence to attempt to make gold alchemically, and a number were granted by Henry VI and Edward IV).
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] These critiques and regulations centered more around pseudo-alchemical charlatanism than the actual study of alchemy, which continued with an increasingly Christian tone.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The 14th century saw the Christian imagery of death and resurrection employed in the alchemical texts of Petrus Bonus, John of Rupescissa, and in works written in the name of Raymond Lull and Arnold of Villanova.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Nicolas Flamel is a well-known alchemist to the point where he had many pseudepigraphic imitators.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Although the historical Flamel existed, the writings and legends assigned to him only appeared in 1612.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] A common idea in European alchemy in the medieval era was a metaphysical "Homeric chain of wise men that link[ed] heaven and earth" that included ancient pagan philosophers and other important historical figures.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] , meaning "redness", was adopted by alchemists and signalled alchemical success, and the end of the great work.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] During the Renaissance, Hermetic and Platonic foundations were restored to European alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The dawn of medical, pharmaceutical, occult, and entrepreneurial branches of alchemy followed.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the late 15th century, Marsilio Ficino translated the Corpus Hermeticum and the works of Plato into Latin.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] These were previously unavailable to Europeans who for the first time had a full picture of the alchemical theory that Bacon had declared absent.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Renaissance Humanism and Renaissance Neoplatonism guided alchemists away from physics to refocus on mankind as the alchemical vessel.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Esoteric systems developed that blended alchemy into a broader occult Hermeticism, fusing it with magic, astrology, and Christian Kabbalah.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] A key figure in this development was Heinrich Cornelius Agrippa (1486–1535), a German who received his Hermetic education in Italy in the schools of the humanists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In his *De Occulta Philosophia*, he attempted to merge Judaism's Kabbalah, Hermeticism, and alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] He was instrumental in spreading this new blend of Hermeticism outside the borders of Italy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Paracelsus, born Philippus Aureolus Theophrastus Bombastus von Hohenheim (1493–1541), cast alchemy into a new form, rejecting some of Agrippa's occultism and moving away from chrysopoeia.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Paracelsus pioneered the use of chemicals and minerals in medicine and wrote, "Many have said of Alchemy, that it is for the making of gold and silver.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] His Hermetical views were that sickness and health in the body relied on the harmony of humankind as the microcosm and Nature the macrocosm.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] He took an approach different from those before him, using this analogy not in the manner of soul-purification but in the manner that humans must have certain balances of minerals in their bodies, and that certain illnesses of the body had chemical remedies that could cure them.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Iatrochemistry refers to the pharmaceutical applications of alchemy championed by Paracelsus.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] John Dee (13 July 1527 – December 1608) followed Agrippa's occult tradition.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Although better known for angel summoning, divination, and his role as astrologer, cryptographer, and consultant to Elizabeth I of England, Dee's alchemical *Monas Hieroglyphica*, written in 1564 was his most popular and influential work.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] His writing portrayed alchemy as a sort of terrestrial astronomy in line with the Hermetic axiom *as above, so below*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] During the 17th century, a short-lived "supernatural" interpretation of alchemy became popular, including support by fellows of the Royal Society: Robert Boyle and Elias Ashmole.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Proponents of the supernatural interpretation of alchemy believed that the philosopher's stone might be used to summon and communicate with angels.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Entrepreneurial opportunities were common for the alchemists of Renaissance Europe.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Alchemists were contracted by the elite for practical purposes related to mining, medical services, and the production of chemicals, medicines, metals, and gemstones.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Rudolf II, Holy Roman Emperor, in the late 16th century, famously received and sponsored various alchemists at his court in Prague, including Dee and his associate Edward Kelley.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] King James IV of Scotland, Julius, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg, Henry V, Duke of Brunswick-Lüneburg, Augustus, Elector of Saxony, Julius Echter von Mespelbrunn, and Maurice, Landgrave of Hesse-Kassel all contracted alchemists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] John's son Arthur Dee worked as a court physician to Michael I of Russia and Charles I of England but also compiled the alchemical book *Fasciculus Chemicus*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Although most of these appointments were legitimate, the trend of pseudo-alchemical fraud continued through the Renaissance.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] *Betrüger* would use sleight of hand, or claims of secret knowledge to make money or secure patronage.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Legitimate mystical and medical alchemists such as Michael Maier and Heinrich Khunrath wrote about fraudulent transmutations, distinguishing themselves from the con artists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] False alchemists were sometimes prosecuted for fraud.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The terms "chemia" and "alchemia" were used as synonyms in the early modern period, and the differences between alchemy, chemistry and small-scale assaying and metallurgy were not as neat as in the present day.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] There were important overlaps between practitioners, and trying to classify them into alchemists, chemists and craftsmen is anachronistic.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] For example, Tycho Brahe (1546–1601), an alchemist better known for his astronomical and astrological investigations, had a laboratory built at his Uraniborg observatory/research institute.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Michael Sendivogius (*Michał Sędziwój*, 1566–1636), a Polish alchemist, philosopher, medical doctor and pioneer of chemistry wrote mystical works but is also credited with distilling oxygen in a lab sometime around 1600.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Sendivogious taught his technique to Cornelius Drebbel who, in 1621, applied this in a submarine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Isaac Newton devoted considerably more of his writing to the study of alchemy (see Isaac Newton's occult studies) than he did to either optics or physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Other early modern alchemists who were eminent in their other studies include Robert Boyle, and Jan Baptist van Helmont.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Their Hermeticism complemented rather than precluded their practical achievements in medicine and science.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The decline of European alchemy was brought about by the rise of modern science with its emphasis on rigorous quantitative experimentation and its disdain for "ancient wisdom".
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Although the seeds of these events were planted as early as the 17th century, alchemy still flourished for some two hundred years, and in fact may have reached its peak in the 18th century.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] As late as 1781 James Price claimed to have produced a powder that could transmute mercury into silver or gold.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Robert Boyle (1627–1691) pioneered the scientific method in chemical investigations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] He assumed nothing in his experiments and compiled every piece of relevant data.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Boyle would note the place in which the experiment was carried out, the wind characteristics, the position of the Sun and Moon, and the barometer reading, all just in case they proved to be relevant.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] This approach eventually led to the founding of modern chemistry in the 18th and 19th centuries, based on revolutionary discoveries and ideas of Lavoisier and John Dalton.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Beginning around 1720, a rigid distinction began to be drawn for the first time between "alchemy" and "chemistry".
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] By the 1740s, "alchemy" was now restricted to the realm of gold making, leading to the popular belief that alchemists were charlatans, and the tradition itself nothing more than a fraud.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In order to protect the developing science of modern chemistry from the negative censure to which alchemy was being subjected, academic writers during the 18th-century scientific Enlightenment attempted to divorce and separate the "new" chemistry from the "old" practices of alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] This move was mostly successful, and the consequences of this continued into the 19th, 20th and 21st centuries.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] During the occult revival of the early 19th century, alchemy received new attention as an occult science.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The esoteric or occultist school that arose during the 19th century held the view that the substances and operations mentioned in alchemical literature are to be interpreted in a spiritual sense, less than as a practical tradition or protoscience.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] This interpretation claimed that the obscure language of the alchemical texts, which 19th century practitioners were not always able to decipher, were an allegorical guise for spiritual, moral or mystical processes.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Two seminal figures during this period were Mary Anne Atwood and Ethan Allen Hitchcock, who independently published similar works regarding spiritual alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Both rebuffed the growing successes of chemistry, developing a completely esoteric view of alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Atwood wrote: "No modern art or chemistry, notwithstanding all its surreptitious claims, has any thing in common with Alchemy." Atwood's work influenced subsequent authors of the occult revival including Eliphas Levi, Arthur Edward Waite, and Rudolf Steiner.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Hitchcock, in his *Remarks Upon Alchymists* (1855) attempted to make a case for his spiritual interpretation with his claim that the alchemists wrote about a spiritual discipline under a materialistic guise in order to avoid accusations of blasphemy from the church and state.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In 1845, Baron Carl Reichenbach, published his studies on Odic force, a concept with some similarities to alchemy, but his research did not enter the mainstream of scientific discussion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In 1946, Louis Cattiaux published the Message Retrouvé, a work that was at once philosophical, mystical and highly influenced by alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In his lineage, many researchers, including Emmanuel and Charles d'Hooghvorst, are updating alchemical studies in France and Belgium.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Several women appear in the earliest history of alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Michael Maier names four women who were able to make the philosophers' stone: Mary the Jewess, Cleopatra the Alchemist, Medera, and Taphnutia.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Zosimos's sister Theosebia (later known as Euthica the Arab) and Isis the Prophetess also played roles in early alchemical texts.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The first alchemist whose name we know was Mary the Jewess (c.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Early sources claim that Mary (or Maria) devised a number of improvements to alchemical equipment and tools as well as novel techniques in chemistry.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Her best known advances were in heating and distillation processes.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The laboratory water-bath, known eponymously (especially in France) as the bain-marie, is said to have been invented or at least improved by her.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Essentially a double-boiler, it was (and is) used in chemistry for processes that required gentle heating.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The tribikos (a modified distillation apparatus) and the kerotakis (a more intricate apparatus used especially for sublimations) are two other advancements in the process of distillation that are credited to her.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Although we have no writing from Mary herself, she is known from the early-fourth-century writings of Zosimos of Panopolis.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] After the Greco-Roman period, women's names appear less frequently in alchemical literature.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Towards the end of the Middle Ages and beginning of the Renaissance, due to the emergence of print, women were able to access the alchemical knowledge from texts of the preceding centuries.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Caterina Sforza, the Countess of Forlì and Lady of Imola, is one of the few confirmed female alchemists after Mary the Jewess.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] As she owned an apothecary, she would practice science and conduct experiments in her botanic gardens and laboratories.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Being knowledgeable in alchemy and pharmacology, she recorded all of her alchemical ventures in a manuscript named *Experimenti* ('Experiments').
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The manuscript contained more than four hundred recipes covering alchemy as well as cosmetics and medicine.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] One of these recipes was for the water of talc.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Talc, which makes up talcum powder, is a mineral which, when combined with water and distilled, was said to produce a solution which yielded many benefits.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] These supposed benefits included turning silver to gold and rejuvenation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] When combined with white wine, its powder form could be ingested to counteract poison.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Furthermore, if that powder was mixed and drunk with white wine, it was said to be a source of protection from any poison, sickness, or plague.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Other recipes were for making hair dyes, lotions, lip colours.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] There was also information on how to treat a variety of ailments from fevers and coughs to epilepsy and cancer.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In addition, there were instructions on producing the quintessence (or aether), an elixir which was believed to be able to heal all sicknesses, defend against diseases, and perpetuate youthfulness.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] She also wrote about creating the illustrious philosophers' stone.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Some women known for their interest in alchemy were Catherine de' Medici, the Queen of France, and Marie de' Medici, the following Queen of France, who carried out experiments in her personal laboratory.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Also, Isabella d'Este, the Marchioness of Mantua, made perfumes herself to serve as gifts.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Due to the proliferation in alchemical literature of pseudepigrapha and anonymous works, however, it is difficult to know which of the alchemists were actually women.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] This contributed to a broader pattern in which male authors credited prominent noblewomen for beauty products with the purpose of appealing to a female audience.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] For example, in *Ricettario galante* ("Gallant Recipe-Book"), the distillation of lemons and roses was attributed to Elisabetta Gonzaga, the duchess of Urbino.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the same book, Isabella d'Aragona, the daughter of Alfonso II of Naples, is accredited for recipes involving alum and mercury.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Ippolita Maria Sforza is even referred to in an anonymous manuscript about a hand lotion created with rose powder and crushed bones.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] As the sixteenth century went on, scientific culture flourished and people began collecting "secrets".
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] During this period "secrets" referred to experiments, and the most coveted ones were not those which were bizarre, but the ones which had been proven to yield the desired outcome.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In this period, the only book of secrets ascribed to a woman was *I secreti della signora Isabella Cortese* ('The Secrets of Signora Isabella Cortese').
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] This book contained information on how to turn base metals into gold, medicine, and cosmetics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] However, it is rumoured that a man, Girolamo Ruscelli, was the real author and only used a female voice to attract female readers.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] In the nineteenth-century, Mary Anne Atwood's *A Suggestive Inquiry into the Hermetic Mystery* (1850) marked the return of women during the occult revival.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The history of alchemy has become a recognized subject of academic study.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] A large collection of books on alchemy is kept in the Bibliotheca Philosophica Hermetica in Amsterdam.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Journals which publish regularly on the topic of Alchemy include *Ambix*, published by the Society for the History of Alchemy and Chemistry, and *Isis*, published by the History of Science Society.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Western alchemical theory corresponds to the worldview of late antiquity in which it was born.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Concepts were imported from Neoplatonism and earlier Greek cosmology.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] As such, the classical elements appear in alchemical writings, as do the seven classical planets and the corresponding seven metals of antiquity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] Similarly, the gods of the Roman pantheon who are associated with these luminaries are discussed in alchemical literature.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The concepts of prima materia and anima mundi are central to the theory of the philosopher's stone.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p02] The Great Work of Alchemy is often described as a series of four stages represented by colours.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Those focusing on the exoteric, such as historians of science Lawrence M.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Newman, have interpreted the *Decknamen* ('code words') of alchemy as physical substances.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] These scholars have reconstructed physicochemical experiments that they say are described in medieval and early modern texts.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] At the opposite end of the spectrum, focusing on the esoteric, scholars, such as Florin George Călian and Anna Marie Roos, who question the reading of Principe and Newman, interpret these same *Decknamen* as spiritual, religious, or psychological concepts.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] New interpretations of alchemy are still perpetuated, sometimes merging with concepts from New Age or radical environmentalism movements.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Groups like the Rosicrucians and Freemasons have a continued interest in alchemy and its symbolism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] In the eyes of a variety of modern esoteric and neo-Hermetic practitioners, alchemy is primarily spiritual.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] In this interpretation, transmutation of lead into gold is presented as an analogy for personal transmutation, purification, and perfection.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] According to this view, early alchemists, such as Zosimos of Panopolis (c.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] 300 AD), highlighted the spiritual nature of the alchemical quest, symbolic of a religious regeneration of the human soul.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] This approach is held to have continued in the Middle Ages, as metaphysical aspects, substances, physical states, and material processes are supposed to have been used as metaphors for spiritual entities, spiritual states, and, ultimately, transformation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] In this sense, the literal meanings of alchemical formulas hid a spiritual philosophy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Applied to the alchemist, the twin goal symbolized their evolution from ignorance to enlightenment, and the stone represented a hidden spiritual truth or power that would lead to that goal.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Alchemical symbolism was important in analytical psychology.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] It was revived and popularized from near extinction by the Swiss psychologist Carl Gustav Jung.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] He observed these alchemical images occurring during the psychic process of transformation, a process that Jung called "individuation".
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Specifically, he regarded the conjuring up of images of gold or Lapis as symbolic expressions of the origin and goal of this "process of individuation".
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Together with his alchemical *mystica soror* (mystical sister), Jungian Swiss analyst Marie-Louise von Franz, Jung began collecting old alchemical texts, compiled a lexicon of key phrases with cross-references, and pored over them.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] His writings are influential in general psychology, especially for those interested in understanding the importance of dreams, symbols, and the unconscious archetypal forces (Jungian archetypes) that comprise all psychic life.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Both von Franz and Jung contributed significantly to the subject and work of alchemy and to its continued presence in psychology and contemporary culture.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Among the volumes Jung wrote on alchemy, his magnum opus is volume 14 of his *Collected Works*, *Mysterium Coniunctionis*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Alchemy has had a long-standing relationship with art, evident in both alchemical texts and mainstream entertainment.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] *Literary alchemy* appears throughout the history of English literature from William Shakespeare to J.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Rowling, and also the popular Japanese manga *Fullmetal Alchemist*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Here, characters or plot structure follow an alchemical magnum opus.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] In the 14th century, Chaucer began a trend of alchemical satire that can still be seen in recent fantasy works, such as those of the late Sir Terry Pratchett.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Another literary work inspired by the alchemical tradition is the 1988 novel *The Alchemist* by Brazilian writer Paulo Coelho.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Visual artists have had a similar relationship with alchemy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] While some used it as a source of satire, others worked with the alchemists themselves or integrated alchemical thought or symbols in their work.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Music was also present in the works of alchemists and continues to influence popular performers.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] In the last hundred years, alchemists have been portrayed in a magical and spagyric role in fantasy fiction, film, television, novels, comics, and video games.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] One goal of alchemy, the transmutation of base substances into gold, is now known to be impossible by means of traditional chemistry, but possible by other physical means.
[src:conservation-of-mass/alchemy-p03] Although not financially worthwhile, gold was synthesized in particle accelerators as early as 1941.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Greek philosophy has influenced much of Western culture since its inception, and can be found in many aspects of public education.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Alfred North Whitehead once claimed: "The safest general characterization of the European philosophical tradition is that it consists of a series of footnotes to Plato".
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Clear, unbroken lines of influence lead from ancient Greek and Hellenistic philosophers to Roman philosophy, early Islamic philosophy, medieval scholasticism, the European Renaissance and the Age of Enlightenment.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Greek philosophy was influenced to some extent by the older wisdom literature and mythological cosmogonies of the ancient Near East, though the extent of this influence is widely debated.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The classicist Martin Litchfield West states, "contact with oriental cosmology and theology helped to liberate the early Greek philosophers' imagination; it certainly gave them many suggestive ideas.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Philosophy as we understand it is a Greek creation".
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] In general, the ancient Greeks acknowledged their Egyptian forebears, and in the fifth century BC, the philosopher Isocrates declared that the earliest Greek thinkers traveled to Egypt to seek knowledge; one of them Pythagoras of Samos, who "was first to bring to the Greeks all philosophy".
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Although Greeks acknowledged Egyptian wisdom, modern scholarship regards Greek philosophy as a distinctive and original intellectual tradition developed independently by Greek thinkers.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Subsequent philosophic tradition was so influenced by Socrates as presented by Plato that it is conventional to refer to philosophy developed prior to Socrates as pre-Socratic philosophy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The periods following this, up to and after the wars of Alexander the Great, are those of "Classical Greek" and "Hellenistic philosophy", respectively.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The **convention** of terming those philosophers who were active prior to the death of Socrates as the *pre-Socratics* gained currency with the 1903 publication of Hermann Diels' *Fragmente der Vorsokratiker*, although the term did not originate with him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Since 2016, however, scholarly discourse has shifted from using the term *"pre-Socratic philosophy"* to the more neutral *"Early Greek Philosophy"*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This change has been popularized in part by André Laks and Glenn W.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Most through their comprehensive nine-volume *Loeb Classical Library* edition of *Early Greek Philosophy*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] In the first volume, they distinguish their systematic approach from that of Hermann Diels, starting with the deliberate choice of terminology.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] They prefer *"Early Greek Philosophy"* over *"pre-Socratic philosophy"* primarily because Socrates was a contemporary of, and in some cases even preceded, thinkers traditionally labeled as "pre-Socratic" such as the Atomists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The early Greek philosophers (or "pre-Socratics") were primarily concerned with cosmology, ontology, and mathematics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] They were distinguished from "non-philosophers" insofar as they rejected mythological explanations in favor of reasoned discourse.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Thales of Miletus, regarded by Aristotle as the first philosopher, held that all things arise from a single material substance, water.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] It is not because he gave a cosmogony that John Burnet calls him the "first man of science", but because he gave a naturalistic explanation of the cosmos and supported it with reasons.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] According to tradition, Thales was able to predict an eclipse and taught the Egyptians how to measure the height of the pyramids.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Thales inspired the Milesian school of philosophy and was followed by Anaximander, who argued that the substratum or *arche* could not be water or any of the classical elements but was instead something "unlimited" or "indefinite" (in Greek, the *apeiron*).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He began from the observation that the world seems to consist of opposites (e.g., hot and cold), yet a thing can become its opposite (e.g., a hot thing cold).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Therefore, they cannot truly be opposites but rather must both be manifestations of some underlying unity that is neither.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This underlying unity (substratum, *arche*) could not be any of the classical elements, since they were one extreme or another.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] For example, water is wet, the opposite of dry, while fire is dry, the opposite of wet.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This initial state is ageless and imperishable, and everything returns to it according to necessity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Anaximenes in turn held that the *arche* was air, although John Burnet argues that by this, he meant that it was a transparent mist, the *aether*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Xenophanes was born in Ionia, where the Milesian school was at its most powerful and may have picked up some of the Milesians' cosmological theories as a result.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Xenophanes was highly influential to subsequent schools of philosophy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He was seen as the founder of a line of philosophy that culminated in Pyrrhonism, possibly an influence on Eleatic philosophy, and a precursor to Epicurus' total break between science and religion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Pythagoras lived at approximately the same time that Xenophanes did and, in contrast to the latter, the school that he founded sought to reconcile religious belief and reason.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Pythagoras is said to have been a disciple of Anaximander and to have imbibed the cosmological concerns of the Ionians, including the idea that the cosmos is constructed of spheres, the importance of the infinite, and that air or aether is the *arche* of everything.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Pythagoreanism also incorporated ascetic ideals, emphasizing purgation, metempsychosis, and consequently a respect for all animal life; much was made of the correspondence between mathematics and the cosmos in a musical harmony.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Pythagoras believed that behind the appearance of things, there was the permanent principle of mathematics, and that the forms were based on a transcendental mathematical relation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Heraclitus must have lived after Xenophanes and Pythagoras, as he condemns them along with Homer as proving that much learning cannot teach a man to think; since Parmenides refers to him in the past tense, this would place him in the 5th century BC.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Contrary to the Milesian school, which posits one stable element as the *arche*, Heraclitus taught that *panta rhei* ("everything flows"), the closest element to this eternal flux being fire.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] All things come to pass in accordance with *Logos*, which must be considered as "plan" or "formula", and "the *Logos* is common".
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He also posited a unity of opposites, expressed through dialectic, which structured this flux, such as that seeming opposites in fact are manifestations of a common substrate to good and evil itself.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Heraclitus called the oppositional processes ἔρις (*eris*), "strife", and hypothesized that the apparently stable state of δίκη (*dikê*), or "justice", is the harmonic unity of these opposites.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Parmenides of Elea cast his philosophy against those who held "it is and is not the same, and all things travel in opposite directions,"—presumably referring to Heraclitus and those who followed him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Whereas the doctrines of the Milesian school, in suggesting that the substratum could appear in a variety of different guises, implied that everything that exists is corpuscular, Parmenides argued that the first principle of being was One, indivisible, and unchanging.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] In support of this, Parmenides' pupil Zeno of Elea attempted to prove that the concept of motion was absurd and as such motion did not exist.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He also attacked the subsequent development of pluralism, arguing that it was incompatible with Being.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] His arguments are known as Zeno's paradoxes.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The power of Parmenides' logic was such that some subsequent philosophers abandoned the monism of the Milesians, Xenophanes, Heraclitus, and Parmenides, where one thing was the *arche*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] In place of this, they adopted pluralism, such as Empedocles and Anaxagoras.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] There were, they said, multiple elements which were not reducible to one another and these were set in motion by love and strife (as in Empedocles) or by Mind (as in Anaxagoras).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Agreeing with Parmenides that there is no coming into being or passing away, genesis or decay, they said that things appear to come into being and pass away because the elements out of which they are composed assemble or disassemble while themselves being unchanging.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Leucippus also proposed an ontological pluralism with a cosmogony based on two main elements: the vacuum and atoms.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] These, by means of their inherent movement, are crossing the void and creating the real material bodies.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] His theories were not well known by the time of Plato, however, and they were ultimately incorporated into the work of his student, Democritus.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Sophism arose from the juxtaposition of *physis* (nature) and *nomos* (law).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] At the same time, nature was constant, while what was by law differed from one place to another and could be changed.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The first person to call themselves a sophist, according to Plato, was Protagoras, whom he presents as teaching that all virtue is conventional.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Protagoras and subsequent sophists tended to teach rhetoric as their primary vocation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Prodicus, Gorgias, Hippias, and Thrasymachus appear in various dialogues, sometimes explicitly teaching that while nature provides no ethical guidance, the guidance that the laws provide is worthless, or that nature favors those who act against the laws.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Socrates, believed to have been born in Athens in the 5th century BC, marks a watershed in ancient Greek philosophy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Athens was a center of learning, with sophists and philosophers traveling from across Greece to teach rhetoric, astronomy, cosmology, and geometry.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The reasons for this turn toward political and ethical subjects remain the object of much study.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The fact that many conversations involving Socrates (as recounted by Plato and Xenophon) end without having reached a firm conclusion, or aporetically, has stimulated debate over the meaning of the Socratic method.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Socrates is said to have pursued this probing question-and-answer style of examination on a number of topics, usually attempting to arrive at a defensible and attractive definition of a virtue.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] While Socrates' recorded conversations rarely provide a definite answer to the question under examination, several maxims or paradoxes for which he has become known recur.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Socrates taught that no one desires what is bad, and so if anyone does something that truly is bad, it must be unwillingly or out of ignorance; consequently, all virtue is knowledge.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He frequently remarks on his own ignorance (claiming that he does not know what courage is, for example).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Plato presents him as distinguishing himself from the common run of mankind by the fact that, while they know nothing noble and good, they do not *know* that they do not know, whereas Socrates knows and acknowledges that he knows nothing noble and good.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Anaxagoras is said to have been charged and to have fled into exile when Socrates was about twenty years of age.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] There is a story that Protagoras, too, was forced to flee and that the Athenians burned his books.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Socrates, however, is the only subject recorded as charged under this law, convicted, and sentenced to death in 399 BC (see Trial of Socrates).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] In the version of his defense speech presented by Plato, he claims that it is the envy he arouses on account of his being a philosopher that will convict him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Numerous subsequent philosophical movements were inspired by Socrates or his younger associates.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Plato casts Socrates as the main interlocutor in his dialogues, deriving from them the basis of Platonism (and by extension, Neoplatonism).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Plato's student Aristotle in turn criticized and built upon the doctrines he ascribed to Socrates and Plato, forming the foundation of Aristotelianism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Antisthenes founded the school that would come to be known as Cynicism and accused Plato of distorting Socrates' teachings.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Zeno of Citium in turn adapted the ethics of Cynicism to articulate Stoicism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Epicurus studied with Platonic and Pyrrhonist teachers before renouncing all previous philosophers (including Democritus, on whose atomism the Epicurean philosophy relies).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The philosophic movements that were to dominate the intellectual life of the Roman Empire were thus born in this febrile period following Socrates' activity, and either directly or indirectly influenced by him.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] They were also absorbed by the expanding Muslim world in the 7th through 10th centuries AD, from which they returned to the West as foundations of Medieval philosophy and the Renaissance, as discussed below.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Plato was an Athenian of the generation after Socrates.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] A further nine dialogues are ascribed to Plato but were considered spurious even in antiquity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Plato's dialogues feature Socrates, although not always as the leader of the conversation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] (One dialogue, the *Laws*, instead contains an "Athenian Stranger".) Along with Xenophon, Plato is the primary source of information about Socrates' life and beliefs and it is not always easy to distinguish between the two.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] While the Socrates presented in the dialogues is often taken to be Plato's mouthpiece, Socrates' reputation for irony, his caginess regarding his own opinions in the dialogues, and his occasional absence from or minor role in the conversation serve to conceal Plato's doctrines.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Much of what is said about his doctrines is derived from what Aristotle reports about them.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The political doctrine ascribed to Plato is derived from the *Republic*, the *Laws*, and the *Statesman*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Although rule by a wise man would be preferable to rule by law, the wise cannot help but be judged by the unwise, and so in practice, rule by law is deemed necessary.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Both the *Republic* and the *Statesman* reveal the limitations of politics, raising the question of what political order would be best given those constraints; that question is addressed in the *Laws*, a dialogue that does not take place in Athens and from which Socrates is absent.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The character of the society described there is eminently conservative, a corrected or liberalized timocracy on the Spartan or Cretan model or that of pre-democratic Athens.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Plato's dialogues also have metaphysical themes, the most famous of which is his theory of forms.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] It holds that non-material abstract (but substantial) forms (or ideas), and not the material world of change known to us through our physical senses, possess the highest and most fundamental kind of reality.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He argued extensively in the *Phaedo*, *Phaedrus*, and *Republic* for the immortality of the soul, and he believed specifically in reincarnation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Plato often uses long-form analogies (usually allegories) to explain his ideas; the most famous is perhaps the Allegory of the Cave.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] It likens most humans to people tied up in a cave, who look only at shadows on the walls and have no other conception of reality.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] If they turned around, they would see what is casting the shadows (and thereby gain a further dimension to their reality).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] If some left the cave, they would see the outside world illuminated by the sun (representing the ultimate form of goodness and truth).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] If these travelers then re-entered the cave, the people inside (who are still only familiar with the shadows) would not be equipped to believe reports of this 'outside world'.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This story explains the theory of forms with their different levels of reality, and advances the view that philosopher-kings are wisest while most humans are ignorant.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] One student of Plato, Aristotle, who would become another of the most influential philosophers of all time, stressed the implication that understanding relies upon first-hand observation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Aristotle moved to Athens from his native Stageira in 367 BC and began to study philosophy (perhaps even rhetoric, under Isocrates), eventually enrolling at Plato's Academy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He left Athens approximately twenty years later to study botany and zoology, became a tutor of Alexander the Great, and ultimately returned to Athens a decade later to establish his own school: the Lyceum.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] At least twenty-nine of his treatises have survived, known as the *corpus Aristotelicum*, and address a variety of subjects including logic, physics, optics, metaphysics, ethics, rhetoric, politics, poetry, botany, and zoology.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Aristotle is often portrayed as disagreeing with his teacher Plato (e.g., in Raphael's School of Athens).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He criticizes the regimes described in Plato's *Republic* and *Laws*, and refers to the theory of forms as "empty words and poetic metaphors".
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He is generally presented as giving greater weight to empirical observation and practical concerns.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Aristotle's fame was not great during the Hellenistic period, when Stoic logic was in vogue, but later peripatetic commentators popularized his work, which eventually contributed heavily to Islamic, Jewish, and medieval Christian philosophy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] His influence was such that Avicenna referred to him simply as "the Master"; Maimonides, Alfarabi, Averroes, and Aquinas as "the Philosopher".
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Aristotle opposed the utopian style of theorizing, deciding to rely on the understood and observed behaviors of people in reality to formulate his theories.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Stemming from an underlying moral assumption that life is valuable, the philosopher makes a point that scarce resources ought to be responsibly allocated to reduce poverty and death.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This 'fear of goods' led Aristotle to exclusively support 'natural' trades in which personal satiation was kept at natural limit of consumption.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] 'Unnatural' trade, as opposed to the intended limit, was classified as the acquisition of wealth to attain more wealth instead of to purchase more goods.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Cutting more along the grain of reality, Aristotle did not only set his mind on how to give people direction to make the right choices but wanted each person equipped with the tools to perform this moral duty.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] In his own words, "Property should be in a certain sense common, but, as a general rule, private; for, when everyone has a distinct interest, men will not complain of one another, and they will make more progress because everyone will be attending to his own business...
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] And further, there is the greatest pleasure in doing a kindness or service to friends or guests or companions, which can only be rendered when a man has private property.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Cynicism was founded by Antisthenes, who was a disciple of Socrates, as well as Diogenes, his contemporary.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Their aim was to live according to nature and against convention.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Antisthenes was inspired by the ascetism of Socrates, and accused Plato of pride and conceit.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Diogenes, his follower, took the ideas to their limit, living in extreme poverty and engaging in anti-social behaviour.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Crates of Thebes was, in turn, inspired by Diogenes to give away his fortune and live on the streets of Athens.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The Cyrenaics were founded by Aristippus of Cyrene, who was a pupil of Socrates.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The Cyrenaics were hedonists and held that pleasure was the supreme good in life, especially physical pleasure, which they thought more intense and more desirable than mental pleasures.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Pleasure is the only good in life and pain is the only evil.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Socrates had held that virtue was the only human good, but he had also accepted a limited role for its utilitarian side, allowing pleasure to be a secondary goal of moral action.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Aristippus and his followers seized upon this, and made pleasure the sole final goal of life, denying that virtue had any intrinsic value.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The Megarian school flourished in the 4th century BC.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] It was founded by Euclides of Megara, one of the pupils of Socrates.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Its ethical teachings were derived from Socrates, recognizing a single good, which was apparently combined with the Eleatic doctrine of Unity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Their work on modal logic, logical conditionals, and propositional logic played an important role in the development of logic in antiquity, and were influences on the subsequent creation of Stoicism and Pyrrhonism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] During the Hellenistic and Roman periods, many different schools of thought developed in the Hellenistic world and then the Greco-Roman world.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Pyrrho of Elis, a Democritean philosopher, traveled to India with Alexander the Great's army where Pyrrho was influenced by Buddhist teachings, most particularly the three marks of existence.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] After returning to Greece, Pyrrho started a new school of philosophy, Pyrrhonism, which taught that it is one's opinions about non-evident matters (i.e., dogma) that prevent one from attaining eudaimonia.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Pyrrhonism places the attainment of ataraxia (a state of equanimity) as the way to achieve eudaimonia.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] To bring the mind to ataraxia Pyrrhonism uses epoché (suspension of judgment) regarding all non-evident propositions.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Pyrrhonists dispute that the dogmatists – which includes all of Pyrrhonism's rival philosophies – have found truth regarding non-evident matters.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] For any non-evident matter, a Pyrrhonist makes arguments for and against such that the matter cannot be concluded, thus suspending belief and thereby inducing ataraxia.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Epicurus studied in Athens with Nausiphanes, who was a follower of Democritus and a student of Pyrrho of Elis.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] He accepted Democritus' theory of atomism, with improvements made in response to criticisms by Aristotle and others.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] His ethics were based on "the pursuit of pleasure and the avoidance of pain".
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This was, however, not simple hedonism, as he noted that "We do not mean the pleasures of the prodigal or of sensuality . . . we mean the absence of pain in the body and trouble in the mind".
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Logic and physics were also part of early Stoicism, further developed by Zeno's successors Cleanthes and Chrysippus.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Their metaphysics was based in materialism, which was structured by logos, reason (but also called God or fate).
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Their logical contributions still feature in contemporary propositional calculus.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Their ethics was based on pursuing happiness, which they believed was a product of 'living in accordance with nature'.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This meant accepting those things which one could not change.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] One could therefore choose whether to be happy or not by adjusting one's attitude towards their circumstances, as the freedom from fears and desires was happiness itself.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Platonism is the philosophy of Plato, asserting the existence of abstract objects, which exist in a realm distinct from both the physical world and the mind.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Central to Platonism is the Theory of Forms, where ideal Forms or perfect archetypes are considered the true reality, with the physical world being an imperfect reflection.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This philosophy has influenced Western thought, emphasizing the difference between the changing, perceptible world and the unchanging, intelligible realm.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Platonism stands in opposition to nominalism, which denies the existence of such abstract entities.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Around 266 BC, Arcesilaus became head of the Platonic Academy, and adopted skepticism as a central tenet of Platonism, making Platonism nearly the same as Pyrrhonism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] After Arcesilaus, Academic skepticism diverged from Pyrrhonism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] This skeptical period of ancient Platonism, from Arcesilaus to Philo of Larissa, became known as the New Academy, although some ancient authors added further subdivisions, such as a Middle Academy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The Academic skeptics did not doubt the existence of truth; they just doubted that humans had the capacities for obtaining it.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] They based this position on Plato's *Phaedo*, sections 64–67, in which Socrates discusses how knowledge is not accessible to mortals.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] While the objective of the Pyrrhonists was the attainment of ataraxia, after Arcesilaus the Academic skeptics did not hold up ataraxia as the central objective.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The Academic skeptics focused on criticizing the dogmas of other schools of philosophy, in particular of the dogmatism of the Stoics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] They acknowledged some vestiges of a moral law within, at best but a plausible guide, the possession of which, however, formed the real distinction between the sage and the fool.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Following the end of the skeptical period of the Academy with Antiochus of Ascalon, Platonic thought entered the period of Middle Platonism, which absorbed ideas from the Peripatetic and Stoic schools.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] More extreme syncretism was done by Numenius of Apamea, who combined it with Neopythagoreanism.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Also affected by the neopythagoreans, the neoplatonists, first of them Plotinus, argued that mind exists before matter, and that the universe has a singular cause which must therefore be a single mind.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] As such, neoplatonism became essentially a religion, and had great impact on Gnosticism and Christian theology.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] During the Middle Ages, Greek ideas were largely forgotten in Western Europe due to the decline in literacy during the Migration Period.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] In the Byzantine Empire, however, Greek ideas were preserved and studied.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] Islamic philosophers such as Al-Kindi (Alkindus), Al-Farabi (Alpharabius), Ibn Sina (Avicenna) and Ibn Rushd (Averroes) also reinterpreted these works after the caliphs authorized the gathering of Greek manuscripts and hired translators to increase their prestige.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] During the High Middle Ages Greek philosophy re-entered the West through both translations from Arabic to Latin and original Greek manuscripts from the Byzantine Empire.
[src:conservation-of-mass/ancient-greek-philosophy] The re-introduction of these philosophies, accompanied by the new Arabic commentaries, had a great influence on Medieval philosophers such as Thomas Aquinas.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The ***annus mirabilis* papers** (from Latin: *annus mirabilis*, lit.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] 'miraculous year') are four papers that Albert Einstein published in the scientific journal **Annalen der Physik** (*Annals of Physics*) in 1905.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] As major contributions to the foundation of modern physics, these scientific publications were the ones for which he gained fame among physicists.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] They revolutionized science's understanding of the fundamental concepts of space, time, mass, and energy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The second paper explained Brownian motion, which established the Einstein relation $D=\mu \,k_{\text{B}}T$ and compelled physicists to accept the existence of atoms.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The third paper introduced Einstein's special theory of relativity, which proclaims the constancy of the speed of light c and derives the Lorentz transformations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein also examined relativistic aberration and the transverse Doppler effect.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The fourth, a consequence of special relativity, developed the principle of mass–energy equivalence, expressed in the equation $E=mc^{2}$ and which led to the discovery and use of nuclear power decades later.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] These four papers, together with quantum mechanics and Einstein's later general theory of relativity, are the foundation of modern physics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] At the time the papers were written, Einstein did not have easy access to a complete set of scientific reference materials, although he did regularly read and contribute reviews to **Annalen der Physik**.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Additionally, scientific colleagues available to discuss his theories were few.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] He worked as an examiner at the Patent Office in Bern, Switzerland, and he later said of a co-worker there, Michele Besso, that he "could not have found a better sounding board for my ideas in all of Europe".
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] In addition, co-workers and the other members of the self-styled "Olympia Academy" (Maurice Solovine and Conrad Habicht) and his wife, Mileva Marić, had some influence on Einstein's work, but how much is unclear.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Through these papers, Einstein tackled some of the era's most important physics questions and problems.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] In 1900, Lord Kelvin, in a lecture titled "Nineteenth-Century Clouds over the Dynamical Theory of Heat and Light", suggested that physics had no satisfactory explanations for the results of the Michelson–Morley experiment and for black body radiation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] As introduced, special relativity provided an account for the results of the Michelson–Morley experiments.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein's explanation of the photoelectric effect extended the quantum theory which Max Planck had developed in his successful explanation of black-body radiation.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Despite the greater fame achieved by his other works, such as that on special relativity, it was his work on the photoelectric effect that won him his Nobel Prize in 1921.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The Nobel committee had waited patiently for experimental confirmation of special relativity; however, none was forthcoming until the time dilation experiments of Ives and Stilwell (1938 and 1941) and Rossi and Hall (1941).
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The article "Über einen die Erzeugung und Verwandlung des Lichtes betreffenden heuristischen Gesichtspunkt" ("On a Heuristic Viewpoint Concerning the Production and Transformation of Light") received 18 March and published 9 June, proposed the idea of *energy quanta*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] In explaining the photoelectric effect, the hypothesis that energy consists of *discrete packets*, as Einstein illustrates, can be directly applied to black bodies, as well.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The idea of light quanta contradicts the wave theory of light that follows naturally from Maxwell's equations for electromagnetic behavior and, more generally, the assumption of infinite divisibility of energy in physical systems.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein noted that the photoelectric effect depended on the wavelength, and hence the frequency of the light.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] At too low a frequency, even intense light produced no electrons.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] However, once a certain frequency was reached, even low intensity light produced electrons.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] He compared this to Planck's hypothesis that light could be emitted only in packets of energy given by *hf*, where *h* is the Planck constant and *f* is the frequency.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] He then postulated that light travels in packets whose energy depends on the frequency, and therefore only light above a certain frequency would bring sufficient energy to liberate an electron.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] By 1921, when Einstein was awarded the Nobel Prize and his work on photoelectricity was mentioned by name in the award citation, some physicists accepted that the equation ( $hf=\Phi +E_{k}$ ) was correct and light quanta were possible.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] In 1923, Arthur Compton's X-ray scattering experiment helped more of the scientific community to accept this formula.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The theory of light quanta was a strong indicator of wave–particle duality, a fundamental principle of quantum mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] A complete picture of the theory of photoelectricity was realized after the maturity of quantum mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein derived expressions for the mean squared displacement of particles.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Using the kinetic theory of gases, which at the time was controversial, the article established that the phenomenon, which had lacked a satisfactory explanation even decades after it was first observed, provided empirical evidence for the reality of the atom.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] It also lent credence to statistical mechanics, which had been controversial at that time, as well.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Before this paper, atoms were recognized as a useful concept, but physicists and chemists debated whether atoms were real entities.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein's statistical discussion of atomic behavior gave experimentalists a way to count atoms by looking through an ordinary microscope.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Wilhelm Ostwald, one of the leaders of the anti-atom school, later told Arnold Sommerfeld that he had been convinced of the existence of atoms by Jean Perrin's subsequent Brownian motion experiments.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein's "Zur Elektrodynamik bewegter Körper" ("On the Electrodynamics of Moving Bodies"), his third paper that year, was received on 30 June and published 26 September.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] It reconciles Maxwell's equations for electricity and magnetism with the laws of mechanics by introducing major changes to mechanics close to the speed of light.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] This later became known as Einstein's special theory of relativity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The paper mentions the names of only five other scientists: Isaac Newton, James Clerk Maxwell, Heinrich Hertz, Christian Doppler, and Hendrik Lorentz.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] It does not have any references to any other publications.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Many of the ideas had already been published by others, as detailed in history of special relativity and relativity priority dispute.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] However, Einstein's paper introduces a theory of time, distance, mass, and energy that was consistent with electromagnetism, but omitted the force of gravity.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] At the time, it was known that Maxwell's equations, when applied to moving bodies, led to asymmetries (moving magnet and conductor problem), and that it had not been possible to discover any motion of the Earth relative to the aether.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein puts forward two postulates to explain these observations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] First, he applies the principle of relativity, which states that the laws of physics remain the same for any non-accelerating frame of reference (called an inertial reference frame), to the laws of electrodynamics and optics as well as mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] In the second postulate, Einstein proposes that the speed of light has the same value in all frames of reference, independent of the state of motion of the emitting body.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The speed of light is fixed, and thus *not* relative to the movement of the observer.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] This was impossible under Newtonian classical mechanics.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] It had previously been proposed, by George FitzGerald in 1889 and by Lorentz in 1892, independently of each other, that the Michelson–Morley result could be accounted for if moving bodies were contracted in the direction of their motion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Some of the paper's core equations, the Lorentz transforms, had been published by Joseph Larmor (1897, 1900), Hendrik Lorentz (1895, 1899, 1904) and Henri Poincaré (1905), in a development of Lorentz's 1904 paper.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein's presentation differed from the explanations given by FitzGerald, Larmor, and Lorentz, but was similar in many respects to the formulation by Poincaré (1905).
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The first is the idea originating with Galileo Galilei that the laws of nature should be the same for all observers that move with constant speed relative to each other.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The second axiom is the rule that the speed of light is the same for every observer.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The theory, now called the special theory of relativity, distinguishes it from his later general theory of relativity, which considers all observers to be equivalent.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Acknowledging the role of Max Planck in the early dissemination of his ideas, Einstein wrote in 1913 "The attention that this theory so quickly received from colleagues is surely to be ascribed in large part to the resoluteness and warmth with which he [Planck] intervened for this theory".
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] In addition, the spacetime formulation by Hermann Minkowski in 1907 was influential in gaining widespread acceptance.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Also, and most importantly, the theory was supported by an ever-increasing body of confirmatory experimental evidence.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] Einstein considered the equivalency equation to be of paramount importance because it showed that a massive particle possesses an energy, the "rest energy", distinct from its classical kinetic and potential energies.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The equation sets forth that the energy of a body at rest (E) equals its mass (m) times the speed of light (c) squared, or *E* = *mc*2.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The mass–energy relation can be used to predict how much energy will be released or consumed by nuclear reactions; one simply measures the mass of all constituents and the mass of all the products and multiplies the difference between the two by *c*2.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The result shows how much energy will be released or consumed, usually in the form of light or heat.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] When applied to certain nuclear reactions, the equation shows that an extraordinarily large amount of energy will be released, millions of times as much as in the combustion of chemical explosives, where the amount of mass converted to energy is negligible.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] This explains why nuclear reactions produce enormous amounts of energy, as they release binding energy during nuclear fission and nuclear fusion, and convert a portion of subatomic mass to energy.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] The International Union of Pure and Applied Physics (IUPAP) resolved to commemorate the 100th year of the publication of Einstein's extensive work in 1905 as the World Year of Physics 2005.
[src:conservation-of-mass/annus-mirabilis-papers] This was subsequently endorsed by the United Nations.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] It is generally accepted that Lavoisier's great accomplishments in chemistry stem largely from his changing the science from a qualitative to a quantitative one.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier is noted for his discovery of the role oxygen plays in combustion, opposing the prior phlogiston theory of combustion.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] He named oxygen (1778), recognizing it as an element, and also recognized hydrogen as an element (1783).
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier helped construct the metric system, wrote the first extensive list of elements, in which he predicted the existence of silicon, and helped to reform chemical nomenclature.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] His wife and laboratory assistant, Marie-Anne Paulze Lavoisier, became a renowned chemist in her own right, and worked with him to develop the metric system of measurements.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] Lavoisier was a powerful member of a number of aristocratic councils, and an administrator of the *Ferme générale*.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] The *Ferme générale* was one of the most hated components of the *Ancien Régime* because of the profits it took at the expense of the state, the secrecy of the terms of its contracts, and the violence of its armed agents.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] All of these political and economic activities enabled him to fund his scientific research.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] At the height of the French Revolution, he was charged with tax fraud and selling adulterated tobacco, and was guillotined despite appeals to spare his life in recognition of his contributions to science.
[src:conservation-of-mass/antoine-lavoisier] A year and a half later, he was exonerated by the French government.
